# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] The **standard atmosphere** (symbol: **atm**) is a unit of pressure defined as 101325 Pa.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] It is sometimes used as a *reference pressure* or *standard pressure*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] It is approximately equal to Earth's average atmospheric pressure at sea level.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] The standard atmosphere was originally defined as the pressure exerted by a 760 mm column of mercury at 0 °C (32 °F) and standard gravity (*g*n = 9.80665 m/s2).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] It was used as a reference condition for physical and chemical properties, and the definition of the centigrade temperature scale set 100 °C as the boiling point of water at this pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] In 1954, the 10th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) adopted *standard atmosphere* for general use and affirmed its definition of being precisely equal to 1013250 dynes per square centimetre (101325 Pa).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] This defined pressure in a way that is independent of the properties of any particular substance.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmosphere-unit] The notation **ata** has been used to indicate an absolute pressure measured in either standard atmospheres (atm) or technical atmospheres (at).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The **atmospheric engine** was invented by Thomas Newcomen in 1712, and is sometimes referred to as the **Newcomen fire engine** (see below) or **Newcomen engine**.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The engine was operated by condensing steam being drawn into the cylinder, thereby creating a partial vacuum which allowed atmospheric pressure to push the piston into the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It is significant as the first practical device to harness steam to produce mechanical work.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen engines were used throughout Britain and Europe, principally to pump water out of mines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Hundreds were constructed during the 18th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] James Watt's later engine design was an improved version of the Newcomen engine that roughly doubled fuel efficiency.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Many atmospheric engines were converted to the Watt design.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] As a result, Watt is today better known than Newcomen in relation to the origin of the steam engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Prior to Newcomen, a number of small steam devices of various sorts had been made, but most were essentially novelties.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Around 1600, a number of experimenters used steam to power small fountains working like a coffee percolator.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] First, a container was filled with water via a pipe, which extended through the top of the container to nearly the bottom.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The bottom of the pipe would be submerged in the water, making the container airtight.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The container was then heated to make the water boil.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The steam generated pressurized the container, but the inner pipe, immersed at the bottom by liquid, and lacking an airtight seal at top, remained at a lower pressure; expanding steam forced the water at the bottom of the container into and up the pipe to spurt out of a nozzle on top.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] These devices had limited effectiveness but illustrated the principle's viability.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In 1606, the Spaniard, Jerónimo de Ayanz y Beaumont, demonstrated and was granted a patent for a steam-powered water pump.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The pump was successfully used to drain the inundated mines of Guadalcanal, Spain.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In 1662, Edward Somerset, 2nd Marquess of Worcester, published a book containing several ideas he had been working on.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] One was for a steam-powered pump to supply water to fountains; the device alternately used a partial vacuum and steam pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Two containers were alternately filled with steam, then sprayed with cold water making the steam within condense; this produced a partial vacuum that would draw water through a pipe up from a well to the container.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] A fresh charge of steam under pressure then drove the water from the container up another pipe to a higher-level header before that steam condensed and the cycle repeated.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] By working the two containers alternately, the delivery rate to the header tank could be increased.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In 1698, Thomas Savery patented a steam-powered pump he called the "Miner's Friend", combining both the expansive power of steam and the vacuum formed through condensation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The process of cooling and creating the vacuum was fairly slow, so Savery later added an external cold water spray to quickly cool the steam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Savery's invention cannot be strictly regarded as the first steam "engine" since it had no moving parts and could not transmit its power to any external device.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] There were evidently high hopes for the Miner's Friend, which led Parliament to extend the life of the patent by 21 years, so that the 1699 patent would not expire until 1733.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Unfortunately, Savery's device proved much less successful than had been hoped.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] A theoretical problem with Savery's device stemmed from the fact that a vacuum could only raise water to a maximum height of about 30 ft (9 m); to this could be added another 40 ft (12 m), or so, raised by steam pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This was insufficient to pump water out of a mine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In Savery's pamphlet, he suggests setting the boiler and containers on a ledge in the mineshaft and even a series of two or more pumps for deeper levels.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Obviously, these were inconvenient solutions and some sort of mechanical pump working at surface level – one that lifted the water directly instead of "sucking" it up – was desirable.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Such pumps were common already, powered by horses, but required a vertical reciprocating drive that Savery's system did not provide.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The more practical problem concerned having a boiler operating under pressure, as demonstrated when the boiler of an engine at Wednesbury exploded, perhaps in 1705.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Engines based on the Savery design, albeit enhanced over time, were installed and used as returning engines, raising water to boost the supply to existing water wheels, examples are known in Manchester and Lancashire.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Louis Figuier in his monumental work gives a full quotation of Denis Papin's paper published in 1690 in *Acta eruditorum* at Leipzig, entitled *"Nouvelle méthode pour obtenir à bas prix des forces considérables"* (A new method for cheaply obtaining considerable forces).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It seems that the idea came to Papin while working with Robert Boyle at the Royal Society in London.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The piston was then temporarily locked in the upper position by a spring catch engaging a notch in the rod.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The fire was then removed, allowing the cylinder to cool, which condensed steam back into water, thus creating a vacuum beneath the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] To the end of the piston rod was attached a cord passing over two pulleys and a weight hung down from the cord's end.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Upon releasing the catch, the piston was sharply drawn down to the bottom of the cylinder by the pressure differential between the atmosphere and the created vacuum; enough force was thus generated to raise a 60 lb (27 kg) weight.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen took forward Papin's experiment and made it workable, although little information exists as to exactly how this came about.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The way forward was to provide, as Savery had, a boiler capable of ensuring the continuity of the supply of steam to the cylinder, providing the vacuum power stroke by condensing the steam, and disposing of the water once it had been condensed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The power piston was hung by chains from the end of a rocking beam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Unlike Savery's device, pumping was entirely mechanical, the work of the steam engine being to lift a weighted rod slung from the opposite extremity of the rocking beam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The rod descended the mine shaft by gravity and drove a force pump, or pole pump (or most often a gang of two) inside the mineshaft.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The suction stroke of the pump was only for the length of the upward (priming) stroke, there consequently was no longer the 30-foot restriction of a vacuum pump and water could be forced up a column from far greater depths.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The boiler supplied the steam at extremely low pressure and was at first located immediately beneath the power cylinder but could also be placed behind a separating wall with a connecting steam pipe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The earliest examples for which reliable records exist were two engines in the Black Country, of which the more famous was that erected in 1712 at the Conygree Coalworks in Bloomfield Road Tipton now the site of "The Angle Ring Company Limited", Tipton.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This is generally accepted as the first successful Newcomen engine and followed by one built a mile and a half east of Wolverhampton.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Both these were used by Newcomen and his partner John Calley to pump out water-filled coal mines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] A working replica can today be seen at the nearby Black Country Living Museum, which stands on another part of what was Lord Dudley's Conygree Park.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Another Newcomen engine was in Cornwall.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Its location is uncertain, but it is known that one was in operation at Wheal Vor mine in 1715.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Soon orders from wet mines all over England were coming in, and some have suggested that word of his achievement was spread through his Baptist connections.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Since Savery's patent had not yet run out, Newcomen was forced to come to an arrangement with Savery and operate under the latter's patent, as its term was much longer than any Newcomen could have easily obtained.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] During the latter years of its currency, the patent belonged to an unincorporated company, *The Proprietors of the Invention for raising water by fire*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Although its first use was in coal-mining areas, Newcomen's engine was also used for pumping water out of the metal mines in his native West Country, such as the tin mines of Cornwall.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] By the time of his death, Newcomen and others had installed over a hundred of his engines, not only in the West Country and the Midlands but also in north Wales, near Newcastle and in Cumbria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Small numbers were built in other European countries, including in France, Belgium, Spain, and Hungary, also at Dannemora, Sweden.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Evidence of the use of a Newcomen Steam Engine associated with early coal mines was found in 2010 in Midlothian, VA (site of some of the first coal mines in the US).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] (Dutton and Associates survey dated 24 November 2009).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Although based on simple principles, Newcomen's engine was rather complex and showed signs of incremental development, problems being empirically addressed as they arose.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It consisted of a boiler **A**, usually a haystack boiler, situated directly below the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This produced large quantities of very low pressure steam, no more than 1–2 psi (0.07–0.14 bar) – the maximum allowable pressure for a boiler that in earlier versions was made of copper with a domed top of lead and later entirely assembled from small riveted iron plates.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The action of the engine was transmitted through a rocking "Great balanced Beam", the fulcrum **E** of which rested on the very solid end-gable wall of the purpose-built engine house with the pump side projecting outside of the building, the engine being located *in-house*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The pump rods were slung by a chain from the arch-head **F** of the great beam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] From the in-house arch-head **D** was suspended a piston **P** working in a cylinder **B**, the top end of which was open to the atmosphere above the piston and the bottom end closed, apart from the short admission pipe connecting the cylinder to the boiler.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Early cylinders were made of cast brass, but cast iron was soon found more effective and much cheaper to produce.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The first to use cast iron was reported to be the engine installed at Hawarden in Wales between 1714 and 1715.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Among the foundries producing and boring iron Newcomen engine cylinders were Coalbrookdale and later the Carron ironworks.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The piston was initially surrounded by a seal in the form of a leather ring, but as the cylinder bore was finished by hand and not absolutely true, a layer of water had to be constantly maintained on top of the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Later soft hemp rope packing was used with iron weights above to keep it in place.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The piston was insulated from the steam, which it would otherwise condense, by bolting wood to the underside.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Installed high up in the engine house was a water tank **C** (or *header tank*) fed by a small in-house pump slung from a smaller arch-head.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The pump equipment was heavier than the steam piston, so that the position of the beam at rest was pump-side down/engine-side up, which was called "out of the house".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] To start the engine, the regulator valve **V** was opened and steam admitted into the cylinder from the boiler, filling the space beneath the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The regulator valve was then closed and the water injection valve **V'** briefly snapped open and shut, sending a spray of cold water into the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This condensed the steam and created a partial vacuum under the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Pressure differential between the atmosphere above the piston and the partial vacuum below then drove the piston down making the power stroke, bringing the beam "into the house", raising the pump gear and pumping the water up from the mine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Steam was then readmitted to the cylinder, destroying the vacuum and driving the condensate down the sinking or "eduction" pipe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] As the low pressure steam from the boiler flowed into the cylinder, the weight of the pump and gear returned the beam to its initial position.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This cycle was repeated around 12 times per minute.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen found that his first engine would stop working after a while, and eventually discovered that this was due to small amounts of air being admitted to the cylinder with the steam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Water usually contains some dissolved air, and boiling the water released this with the steam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This air could not be condensed by the water spray and gradually accumulated until the engine became "wind logged".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] To prevent this, a release valve called a "snifting clack" or snifter valve was included near the bottom of the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This opened briefly when steam was first introduced, and non-condensable gas was driven from the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Its name was derived from the noise it made when it operated to release the air and steam "like a Man snifting with a Cold".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In early versions, the valves or *plugs* as they were then called, were operated manually by the *plug man* but the repetitive action demanded precise timing, making automatic action desirable.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] On the 1712 engine, the water feed pump was attached to the bottom of the plug tree, but later engines had the pump outside suspended from a separate small arch-head.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Because of the very heavy steam demands, the engine had to be periodically stopped and restarted, but even this process was automated by means of a buoy rising and falling in a vertical stand pipe fixed to the boiler.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The buoy was attached to the *scoggen*, a weighted lever that worked a stop blocking the water injection valve shut until more steam had been raised.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The design of pumps used for coal mines with Newcomen engines are discussed in some detail in John Farey's book "A treatise on the steam engine", published in 1827.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Water is rarely raised to the surface, but instead is pumped from the base of the shaft to an adit level which is a slowly descending shaft driven to a suitable low point to discharge the water.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] At the base of the shaft the pump draws water into the base section by suction (the pump is called a sucking pump as a result), and thence above a non-return valve into the main pump body.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The pump piston incorporates a valve which opens on the downstroke and then closes lifting the column of water above into a column made of iron pipes joined with lead gaskets.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The normal maximum lift is 50 yards due to the water pressure in the iron pipes, which have to be strong enough to withstand the pressure and a degree of shock.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The pump rod may be divided to operate multiple pumps to overcome this limitation, each one lifting water into a cistern which feeds into the pump above.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] One particular consideration is to make sure the pumps do not draw in air as the resulting shocks can damage the pump system and the engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Towards the close of its career, the atmospheric engine was much improved in its mechanical details and its proportions by John Smeaton, who built many large engines of this type during the 1770s.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The urgent need for an engine to give rotary motion was making itself felt and this was done with limited success by Wasborough and Pickard using a Newcomen engine to drive a flywheel through a crank.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] By 1725 the Newcomen engine was in common use in mining, particularly collieries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It held its place with little material change for the rest of the century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Use of the Newcomen engine was extended in some places to pump municipal water supply; for instance the first Newcomen engine in France was built at Passy in 1726 to pump water from the Seine to the city of Paris.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It was also used to power machinery indirectly, by returning water from below a water wheel to a reservoir above it, so that the same water could again turn the wheel.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Among the earliest examples of this was at Coalbrookdale.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] A horse-powered pump had been installed in 1735 to return water to the pool above the Old Blast Furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This was replaced by a Newcomen engine in 1742–3.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Several new furnaces built in Shropshire in the 1750s were powered in a similar way, including Horsehay and Ketley Furnaces and Madeley Wood or Bedlam Furnaces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The latter does not seem to have had a pool above the furnace, merely a tank into which the water was pumped.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In other industries, engine-pumping was less common, but Richard Arkwright used an engine to provide additional power for his cotton mill.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Attempts were made to drive machinery by Newcomen engines, but the engines weren't well suited to this work as the delay between power strokes produced a very jerky motion.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] There were attempts to smooth the motion by making Newcomen engines with two cylinders which acted on the crank alternately, the two main firms offering these being Francis Thompson of Ashover, Derbyshire (who patented the idea in 1793), and Batemen and Sherratt of Manchester.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The main problem with the Newcomen design was that it used energy inefficiently, and was therefore expensive to operate.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] After the water vapor within was cooled enough to create the vacuum, the cylinder walls were cold enough to condense some of the steam as it was admitted during the next intake stroke.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This meant that a considerable amount of fuel was being used just to heat the cylinder back to the point where the steam would start to fill it again.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] As the heat losses were related to the surfaces, while useful work related to the volume, increases in the size of the engine increased efficiency, and Newcomen engines became larger in time.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] However, efficiency did not matter very much within the context of a colliery, where coal was freely available.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Newcomen's engine was only replaced when James Watt improved it in 1769 to avoid this problem (Watt had been asked to repair a model of a Newcomen engine by Glasgow University—a small model that exaggerated the problem).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In the Watt steam engine, condensation took place in an exterior condenser unit, attached to the steam cylinder via a pipe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] When a valve on the pipe was opened, the vacuum in the condenser would, in turn, evacuate that part of the cylinder below the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This eliminated the cooling of the main cylinder walls and such, and dramatically reduced fuel use.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It also enabled the development of a double-acting cylinder, with both upwards and downwards power strokes, increasing amount of power from the engine without a great increase in the size of the engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Watt's prototype engine in 1769, revealed that he needed a step-change in precision for the cylinders.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In the Newcomen engine the seal could be effected with copious amounts of water, but Watt's cylinder had to operate without the water flood as the idea was to maintain the cylinder at steam temperature.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Watt could not make his engines until 1774, when John Wilkinson devised an accurate cylinder boring method, and was given an exclusive contract for producing the cylinders as a result.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In 1776 Watt wrote to Smeaton that "Mr Wilkinson has improved the art of boring cylinders; so that I promise upon a 72 inch cylinder being not further distant from absolute truth, than the thickness of a slim sixpence in the worst part".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Boulton and Watt production started the very next year, but the new engines did not eliminate Newcomen engines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Watt's vigorous defence of his patents resulted in the continued use of the Newcomen engine in an effort to avoid royalty payments.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Boulton and Watt relied on others to make the engine parts (e.g.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] John Wilkinson) until 1795 and this resulted in delays, plus they favoured a contract with ongoing payments based on the amount of coal saved.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Competitors such as Bateman (from 1791 Bateman and Sherratt) had their own foundry in Salford and built many atmospheric engines, many breaching Watt's patent, leading to a court case in 1796 and a substantial settlement, but Boulton & Watt refused to let them licence the separate condenser.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] However Bateman and Sherratt, and others, continued to sell atmospheric engines, some designed to use the separate condenser when the Watt patent expired.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] When the patents expired in 1800, there was a rush to use the separate condenser and so the remaining Newcomen engines were adapted or replaced, even in collieries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] However the use of atmospheric engines, albeit with the Watt separate condenser, was to continue for many years as the use of high-pressure steam boilers was in its early stages, and as yet unproven.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The Newcomen Memorial Engine can be seen operating in Newcomen's home town of Dartmouth, where it was moved in 1963 by the Newcomen Society.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This is believed to date from 1725, when it was initially installed at the Griff Colliery near Coventry.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] An engine was installed at a colliery in Ashton-under-Lyne in about 1760.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Known locally as *Fairbottom Bobs* it is now preserved at the Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn, Michigan.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The only Newcomen-style engine still extant in its original location is at what is now the Elsecar Heritage Centre, near Barnsley in South Yorkshire.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] This was probably the last commercially used Newcomen-style engine, as it ran from 1795 until 1923.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The engine underwent extensive conservation works, together with its original shaft and engine-house, which were completed in autumn 2014.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] There are two static examples of a Newcomen Engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] A second example is in the National Museum of Scotland.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Formerly at Caprington Colliery at Kilmarnock.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Another example, originally used at Farme Colliery is on display at Summerlee, Museum of Scottish Industrial Life; unusually it was used for winding rather than water pumping, and had been in operation for almost a century when examined in situ in 1902.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] In 1986, a full-scale operational replica of the 1712 Newcomen Steam Engine was completed at the Black Country Living Museum in Dudley.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] It is the only full-size working replica of the engine in existence and is believed to be a couple of miles away from the site of the first completed engine, erected in 1712.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The 'fire engine' as it was known, is an impressive brick building from which a wooden beam projects through one wall.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] Rods hang from the outer end of the beam and operate pumps at the bottom of the mine shaft which raise the water to the surface.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The engine itself is simple, with only a boiler, a cylinder and piston and operating valves.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] A coal fire heats the water in the boiler which is little more than a covered pan and the steam generated then passes through a valve into the brass cylinder above the boiler.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The cylinder is more than 2 metres long and 52 centimetres in diameter.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-engine] The steam in the cylinder is condensed by injecting cold water and the vacuum beneath the piston pulls the inner end of the beam down and causes the pump to move.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Because the atmosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius – especially the dense atmospheric layer at low altitudes – the Earth's gravitational acceleration as a function of altitude can be approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square meter, 1 N/m2).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in2 would have a weight of about 14.7 lbf, resulting in a pressure of 14.7 lbf/in2.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the planet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the mass of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] It is modified by the planetary rotation and local effects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and variations in composition.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The *mean sea-level pressure* (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] This is the atmospheric pressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, television, and newspapers or on the Internet.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The *altimeter setting* in aviation is an atmospheric pressure adjustment.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] In aviation weather reports (METAR), QNH is transmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal = 1 millibar).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] In the United States, Canada, and Japan altimeter setting is reported in inches of mercury (to two decimal places).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The United States and Canada also report *sea-level pressure* SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, in hectopascals or millibars.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is instead reported in kilopascals.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are transmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omitted: 1,013.2 hPa (14.695 psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000 hPa (100 kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7 hPa is transmitted as 987; etc.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] A system transmitting the last three digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The highest *sea-level pressure* on Earth occurs in Siberia, where the Siberian High often attains a *sea-level pressure* above 1,050 hPa (15.2 psi; 31 inHg), with record highs close to 1,085 hPa (15.74 psi; 32.0 inHg).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest measurable *sea-level pressure* is found at the centres of tropical cyclones and tornadoes, with a record low of 870 hPa (12.6 psi; 26 inHg).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as general circulation models (GCMs) usually predict the nondimensional *logarithm of surface pressure*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] This is in contrast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressure to sea level for locations above or below sea level.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The average pressure at mean sea level (MSL) in the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) is 1,013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are related by P = F/A = (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric mass above that location.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressure on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure varies smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the mesosphere.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Although the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditions for all parts of the earth year-round.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] As altitude increases, atmospheric pressure decreases.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a given altitude.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Temperature and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure is proportional to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are necessary to compute an accurate figure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The graph on the rightabove was developed for a temperature of 15 °C and a relative humidity of 0%.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.2 kPa (12 hPa) for every 100 meters.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and differences in pressure are important in studying weather and climate.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Some variations in pressure are very regular.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] One important source of variation is atmospheric tides.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric tides are strongest in tropical zones, with an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Tropical tidal variations in pressure consist principally of two superimposed harmonics – a circadian (24 h) cycle and a semi-circadian (12 h) cycle.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on Earth above 750 meters was 1,084.8 hPa (32.03 inHg; 1.0706 atm), measured in Tosontsengel, Mongolia on 19 December 2001.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded below 750 meters was at Agata, in Evenk Autonomous Okrug, Russia (66°53' N, 93°28' E, elevation: 261 m, 856 ft), on 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8 hPa (32.005 inHg).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The Dead Sea, the lowest sea surface on Earth, at 430 metres (1,410 ft) below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure of 1,065 hPa.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1,081.8 hPa (31.95 inHg; 1.0677 atm) was set on 21 February 1961.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870 hPa (26 inHg; 0.86 atm), set on 12 October 1979, during Typhoon Tip in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The measurement was based on an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] One atmosphere (101.325 kPa or 14.7 psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of freshwater of approximately 10.3 m (33.8 ft).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Thus, a diver 10.3 m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1 atm of air plus 1 atm of water).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, 10.3 m is the maximum height to which water can be raised using suction under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Low pressures, such as natural gas lines, are sometimes specified in inches of water, typically written as *w.c.* (water column) gauge or *w.g.* (inches water) gauge.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] A typical gas-using residential appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of 1⁄2 psi (3.4 kPa; 34 mbar), which is approximately 14 w.g.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Similar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on millimeters, centimeters or meters are now less commonly used.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Pure water boils at 100 °C (212 °F) at Earth's standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapour pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure around the liquid.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower pressure and higher at higher pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Cooking at high elevations, therefore, requires adjustments to recipes or pressure cooking.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the temperature at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for example in distillation, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using a vacuum pump, as in a rotary evaporator.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure varies directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mountains, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] In 1774, Nevil Maskelyne was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on Schiehallion mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations on the mountain's sides accurately.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] This event is known as the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] William Roy, using barometric pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agreement was within one meter (3.28 feet).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/atmospheric-pressure] This method became and continues to be useful for survey work and map making.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The area of today's Austria has been inhabited since at least the Paleolithic period.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Around 400 BC, it was inhabited by the Celts and then annexed by the Romans in the late 1st century BC.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Christianization in the region began in the 4th and 5th centuries, during the late Roman period, followed by the arrival of numerous Germanic tribes during the Migration Period.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria, as an unified state, emerged from the remnants of the Eastern and Hungarian March at the end of the first millennium, first as a frontier march of the Holy Roman Empire, it then developed into a Duchy in 1156, and was made an Archduchy in 1453.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Being the heartland of the Habsburg monarchy since the late 13th century, Austria was a major imperial power in Central Europe for centuries and from the 16th century, Vienna also served as the Holy Roman Empire's administrative capital.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Holy Roman Empire was dissolved in 1806, two years after Austria had established its own empire, which became a great power and one of the largest states in Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The empire's defeat in wars and the loss of territories in the 1860s paved the way for the establishment of Austria-Hungary in 1867.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] After the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in 1914, Emperor Franz Joseph declared war on Serbia, which rapidly escalated into World War I.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The empire's defeat and subsequent collapse led to the proclamation of the Republic of German-Austria in 1918 and the First Austrian Republic in 1919.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] During the interwar period, anti-parliamentarian sentiments culminated in the formation of an Austrofascist dictatorship under Engelbert Dollfuss in 1934.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] A year before the outbreak of World War II, Austria was annexed into Nazi Germany by Adolf Hitler, and it became a sub-national division.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] After its liberation in 1945 and a decade of Allied occupation, the country regained its sovereignty and declared its perpetual neutrality in 1955.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria is a semi-presidential representative democracy with a popularly elected president as head of state and a chancellor as head of government and chief executive.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria has the 13th highest nominal GDP per capita with high standards of living.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The country has been a member of the United Nations since 1955 and of the European Union since 1995.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] It hosts the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) and the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and is a founding member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and Interpol.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] It also signed the Schengen Agreement in 1995, and adopted the euro currency in 1999.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The native name for Austria, *Österreich*, derives from the Old High German *Ostarrîchi*, which meant "eastern realm", can be also translated as "eastern empire" or "eastern kingdom", and which first appeared in the "Ostarrîchi document" of 996.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This word is probably a translation of Medieval Latin *Marchia orientalis* into a local (Bavarian) dialect.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria was a prefecture of Bavaria created in 976.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The word "Austria" is a Latinisation of the German name and was first recorded in the 12th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] At the time, the Danube basin of Austria (Upper and Lower Austria) was the easternmost extent of Bavaria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The area that is now Austria was settled in pre-Roman times by various Celtic tribes, having been the core of the Hallstatt culture by the 6th century BC.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The city of Hallstatt, in fact, has the oldest archaeological evidence of the Celts in Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Celtic Kingdom of Noricum that included most of modern Austria and parts of modern Slovenia was conquered by the Roman Empire in 16 BC and made a province called Noricum which lasted until 476.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The regions of today's Austria which were not located within the province of Noricum were divided between the Roman provinces of Pannonia, which encompassed parts of eastern Austria, and Raetia, which encompassed the areas of present-day Vorarlberg and Tyrol.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Present-day Petronell-Carnuntum in eastern Austria was an important army camp turned capital city in what became known as the Pannonia Superior.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Carnuntum was home to 50,000 people for nearly 400 years.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the area was first invaded by the Germanic Rugii which made this region part of their "Rugiland".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 487, most of modern Austria was conquered by Odoacer, a barbarian soldier and statesman from the Middle Danube, which incorporated most of today's Austria in his Kingdom of Italy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] By 493, it was conquered by the Germanic Ostrogoths which created their own kingdom, the Ostrogothic Kingdom.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Following the Kingdom's fall the area was invaded by the Alemanni, Baiuvarii, Slavs, and Avars.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Charlemagne, King of the Franks, conquered the area in 788, encouraged colonisation, and introduced Christianity.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As part of Eastern Francia, the core areas that now encompass Austria were bequeathed to the house of Babenberg.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The area was known as the *marchia Orientalis* and was given to Leopold I in 976.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The first record showing the name Austria is from 996, where it is written as *Ostarrîchi*, referring to the territory of the Babenberg March.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1156, the Privilegium Minus elevated Austria to the status of a duchy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1192, the Babenbergs also acquired the Duchy of Styria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] With the death of Frederick II in 1246, the line of the Babenbergs was extinguished.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As a result, Ottokar II of Bohemia effectively assumed control of the duchies of Austria, Styria, and Carinthia.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] His reign came to an end with his defeat at Dürnkrut at the hands of Rudolph I of Germany in 1278.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Thereafter, until World War I, Austria's history was largely that of its ruling dynasty, the Habsburgs.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In the 14th and 15th centuries, the Habsburgs began to accumulate other provinces in the vicinity of the Duchy of Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1438, Duke Albert V of Austria was chosen as the successor to his father-in-law, Emperor Sigismund.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Although Albert himself only reigned for a year, henceforth every emperor of the Holy Roman Empire was a Habsburg, with only one exception.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Habsburgs also began to accumulate territory far from the hereditary lands.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1477, Archduke Maximilian, only son of Emperor Frederick III, married the heiress Maria of Burgundy, thus acquiring most of the Netherlands for the family.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1496, his son Philip the Fair married Joanna the Mad, the heiress of Castile and Aragon, thus acquiring Spain and its Italian, African, Asian, and New World appendages for the Habsburgs.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1526, following the Battle of Mohács, Bohemia and the part of Hungary not occupied by the Ottomans came under Austrian rule.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Ottoman expansion into Hungary led to frequent conflicts between the two empires, particularly evident in the Long War of 1593 to 1606.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Turks made incursions into Styria nearly 20 times, of which some are cited as "burning, pillaging, and taking thousands of slaves".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In late September 1529, Suleiman the Magnificent launched the first siege of Vienna, which unsuccessfully ended, according to Ottoman historians, with the snowfalls of an early beginning winter.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] During the long reign of Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor following the successful defence of Vienna against the Turks in 1683, under the command of the King of Poland John III Sobieski, the Great Turkish War resulted in most of Hungary being controlled by Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This arrangement was formalized in the Treaty of Karlowitz in 1699.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor relinquished many of the gains the empire made in the previous years.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He enjoyed the imminent extinction of the House of Habsburg.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Charles VI was willing to offer concrete advantages in territory and authority in exchange for recognition of the Pragmatic Sanction of 1713.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Therefore, his daughter Maria Theresa was recognized as his heir.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] With the rise of Prussia, the Austria–Prussia rivalry began in Germany.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria participated, together with Prussia and Russia, in the first and the third of the three Partitions of Poland in 1772 and 1795 respectively.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria engaged in war with Revolutionary France, as part of the First and Second Coalitions, and subsequently in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] From 1792 to 1801, the Austrians had suffered 754,700 casualties.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Hapsburg rulers of Austria and the Holy Roman Empire suffered successive defeats at the hands of Napoleon Bonaparte.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] To protect their status as an imperial dynasty after Napoleon proclaimed the French Empire, the Empire of Austria was founded in 1804, and to prevent Napoleon from claiming their previous Imperial throne, the Holy Roman Empire was abolished 1806.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1814, Austria was part of the coalition of Allied forces that invaded France and brought to an end the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian Empire emerged from the Congress of Vienna in 1815 as one of the continent's four dominant powers and a recognized great power.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The same year, the German Confederation (*Deutscher Bund*) was founded under the presidency of Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Because of unsolved social, political, and national conflicts, the German lands were shaken by the 1848 revolutions aiming to create a unified Germany.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The possibilities for a unified Germany were: a Greater Germany or a Greater Austria or a German Confederation without Austria at all.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1864, Austria and Prussia fought together against Denmark and secured the independence from Denmark of the duchies of Schleswig and Holstein.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As they could not agree on how the two duchies should be administered, though they fought the Austro-Prussian War in 1866.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Defeated by Prussia in the Battle of Königgrätz, Austria had to leave the German Confederation and no longer took part in German politics.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As Austria's Habsburg monarchy was not willing to join its German-speaking territory to the German Empire of 1871, and relinquish its non-German-speaking territories, the crown of the newly formed empire was offered to the Prussian King Friedrich Wilhelm IV.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] To settle issues lingering from the suppressed Hungarian Revolution of 1848, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867, the *Ausgleich*, provided for a dual sovereignty, the Austrian Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary, under Franz Joseph I.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian-Hungarian rule of this diverse empire included various groups, including Germans, Hungarians, Croats, Czechs, Poles, Rusyns, Serbs, Slovaks, Slovenes, and Ukrainians, as well as large Italian and Romanian communities.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As a result, ruling Austria-Hungary became increasingly difficult in an age of emerging nationalist movements, requiring considerable reliance on an expanded secret police.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Many Austrian Germans of all different social circles such as Georg Ritter von Schönerer promoted strong pan-Germanism in the hope of reinforcing an ethnic German identity amongst Austrian Germans and the annexation of Austria to Germany (*Anschluss*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Some Austrians such as Karl Lueger also used pan-Germanism as a form of populism to further their own political goals.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria's exclusion from Germany caused many Austrians a problem with their national identity and prompted the Social Democratic Leader Otto Bauer to state that it was "the conflict between our Austrian and German character".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Empire caused ethnic tension between the German Austrians and the other ethnic groups.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Many Austrians, especially those involved with the pan-German movements, desired a reinforcement of an ethnic German identity and hoped that the empire would collapse, which would allow an annexation of Austria by Germany.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Many Austrian pan-German nationalists protested passionately against minister-president Kasimir Count Badeni's language decree of 1897, which made German and Czech co-official languages in Bohemia and required new government officials to be fluent in both languages.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This meant in practice that the civil service would almost exclusively hire Czechs because most middle-class Czechs spoke German but not the other way around.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The support of ultramontane Catholic politicians and clergy for this reform triggered the launch of the *Away from Rome* movement, which was initiated by supporters of Schönerer and called on "German" Christians to leave the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As the Second Constitutional Era began in the Ottoman Empire, Austria-Hungary took the opportunity to annex Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1908.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Over one million Austro-Hungarian soldiers died in World War I.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 21 October 1918, the elected German members of the *Reichsrat* (parliament of Imperial Austria) met in Vienna as the Provisional National Assembly for German Austria (*Provisorische Nationalversammlung für Deutschösterreich*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 30 October the assembly founded the Republic of German-Austria by appointing a government, called *Staatsrat*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This new government was invited by the Emperor to take part in the decision on the planned armistice with Italy but refrained from this business.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This left the responsibility for the end of the war, on 3 November 1918, solely to the emperor and his government.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 11 November, the emperor, advised by ministers of the old and the new governments, declared he would not take part in state business any more; on 12 November, German-Austria, by law, declared itself to be a democratic republic and part of the new German republic.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The constitution, renaming the *Staatsrat* as *Bundesregierung* (federal government) and *Nationalversammlung* as *Nationalrat* (national council) was passed on 10 November 1920.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Treaty of Saint-Germain of 1919 (for Hungary the Treaty of Trianon of 1920) confirmed and consolidated the new order of Central Europe which to a great extent had been established in November 1918, creating new states and altering others.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The German-speaking parts of Austria which had been part of Austria-Hungary were reduced to a rump state named the Republic of German-Austria (German: *Republik Deutschösterreich*), though excluding the predominantly German-speaking South Tyrol.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The desire for the annexation of Austria to Germany was a popular opinion shared by all social circles in both Austria and Germany.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 12 November, German-Austria was declared a republic, and named Social Democrat Karl Renner as provisional chancellor.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On the same day it drafted a provisional constitution that stated that "German-Austria is a democratic republic" (Article 1) and "German-Austria is an integral part of the German Reich" (Article 2).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Treaty of Saint Germain and the Treaty of Versailles explicitly forbade union between Austria and Germany.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The treaties also forced German-Austria to rename itself as "Republic of Austria" which consequently led to the first Austrian Republic.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Over three million German-speaking Austrians found themselves living outside the new Austrian Republic as minorities in the newly formed or enlarged states of Czechoslovakia, Yugoslavia, Hungary, and Italy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] These included the provinces of South Tyrol, and German Bohemia.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The status of German Bohemia and Sudetenland later played a role in World War II.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The border between Austria and the Kingdom of Yugoslavia was settled with the Carinthian Plebiscite in October 1920 and allocated the major part of the territory of the former Austro-Hungarian Crownland of Carinthia to Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This set the border on the Karawanks mountain range, with many Slovenes remaining in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] After the war, inflation began to devalue the Krone, which was still Austria's currency.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In the autumn of 1922, Austria was granted an international loan supervised by the League of Nations.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The purpose of the loan was to avert bankruptcy, stabilise the currency, and improve Austria's general economic condition.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The loan meant that Austria passed from an independent state to the control exercised by the League of Nations.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1925, the *Austrian schilling* was introduced, replacing the Krone at a rate of 10,000:1.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Later, it was nicknamed the "Alpine dollar" due to its stability.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] From 1925 to 1929 the economy enjoyed a short high before nearly crashing after Black Tuesday.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The First Austrian Republic lasted until 1933, when Chancellor Engelbert Dollfuss, using what he called "self-switch-off of Parliament", established an autocratic regime tending towards Italian fascism.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The two big parties at this time, the Social Democrats and the Conservatives, had paramilitary armies; the Social Democrats' *Republikanischer Schutzbund* was now declared illegal, but was still operative as the 12–15 February 1934 Austrian Civil War broke out.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In February 1934, several members of the *Schutzbund* were executed, the Social Democratic party was outlawed, and many of its members were imprisoned or emigrated.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 1 May 1934, the Austrofascists imposed a new constitution ("Maiverfassung") which cemented Dollfuss's power, but on 25 July he was assassinated in an Austrian Nazi coup attempt.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] His successor Kurt Schuschnigg acknowledged the fact that Austria was a "German state" and he also believed that Austrians were "better Germans" but he wished that Austria would remain independent.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He announced a referendum on 9 March 1938, to be held on 13 March, concerning Austria's independence from Germany.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 12 March 1938, Austrian Nazis took over the government, while German troops occupied the country, which prevented Schuschnigg's referendum from taking place.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] 'joining' or 'connection') of Austria was officially declared.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Two days later, Austrian-born Adolf Hitler announced what he called the "reunification" of his home country with the "rest of the German Reich" on Vienna's Heldenplatz.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He established a referendum which confirmed the union with Germany in April 1938.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Parliamentary elections were held in Germany (including recently annexed Austria) on 10 April 1938.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] They were the final elections to the Reichstag during Nazi rule, and they took the form of a single-question referendum asking whether voters approved of a single Nazi-party list for the 813-member Reichstag, as well as the recent annexation of Austria (the *Anschluss*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Jews, Roma and Sinti were not allowed to vote.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Turnout in the election was officially 99.5%, with 98.9% voting "yes".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In the case of Austria, Adolf Hitler's native soil, 99.71% of an electorate of 4,484,475 officially went to the ballots, with a positive tally of 99.73 percent.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Although most Austrians favoured the *Anschluss*, in certain parts of Austria, the German soldiers were not always welcomed with flowers and joy, especially in Vienna, which had Austria's largest Jewish population.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 13 March 1938, Austria was annexed by the Third Reich and ceased to exist as an independent country (the *Anschluss*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Aryanisation of the wealth of Jewish Austrians started immediately in mid-March, with a so-called "wild" (i.e. extra-legal) phase, but it was soon structured legally and bureaucratically so the assets which Jewish citizens possessed could be stripped from them.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] At that time, Adolf Eichmann, who grew up in Austria, was transferred to Vienna and ordered to persecute the Jews.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] During the November pogrom in 1938 ("Reichskristallnacht"), Jews and Jewish institutions such as synagogues were subjected to violent attacks in Vienna, Klagenfurt, Linz, Graz, Salzburg, Innsbruck and several cities in Lower Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Otto von Habsburg, a vehement opponent of the Nazis, the last Crown Prince of Austria-Hungary, an honorary citizen of hundreds of places in Austria and partly envisaged by Schuschnigg as a monarchical option, was in Belgium at the time.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He spoke out against the Anschluss and was then wanted by the Nazi regime and his property would have been expropriated and he would have been shot immediately if he were caught.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 1938, the Nazis renamed Austria the "Ostmark", a name which it had until 1942, when it was renamed the "Alpine and Danubian Gaue" (Alpen-und Donau-Reichsgaue).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In the Reichsgau, besides the main camp KZ-Mauthausen, there were numerous sub-camps in all provinces where Jews and other prisoners were killed, tortured and exploited.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] At this time, because the territory was outside the operational radius of Allied aircraft, the armaments industry was greatly expanded through the forced labour of concentration camp prisoners, this was especially the case with regard to the manufacture of fighter planes, tanks and missiles.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Most of the resistance groups were soon crushed by the Gestapo.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] While the plans of the group around Karl Burian to blow up the Gestapo's headquarters in Vienna were uncovered, the important group around the later executed priest Heinrich Maier managed to contact the Allies.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This resistance group, which was in contact with the American secret service (OSS), soon provided information about mass executions and concentration camps such as Auschwitz.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The group's aim was to cause Nazi Germany to lose the war as quickly as possible and re-establish an independent Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Vienna fell on 13 April 1945, during the Soviet Vienna offensive, just before the total collapse of the Third Reich.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The invading Allied powers, in particular the Americans, planned for the supposed "Alpine Fortress Operation" of a national redoubt, that was largely to have taken place on Austrian soil in the mountains of the Eastern Alps.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] However, it never materialised because of the rapid collapse of the Reich.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] (The date is officially named the birthday of the second republic.) At the end of April, most of western and southern Austria were still under Nazi rule.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 1 May 1945, the Federal Constitutional Law of 1920, which had been terminated by dictator Dollfuss on 1 May 1934, was declared valid again.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The total number of Austrian military deaths from 1939 to 1945 was 260,000.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The total number of Jewish Austrian Holocaust victims was 65,000.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] About 140,000 Jewish Austrians had fled from the country in 1938–39.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Thousands of Austrians had taken part in serious Nazi crimes (hundreds of thousands of people died in the Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp alone), a fact which was officially acknowledged by Chancellor Franz Vranitzky in 1992.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Allied-occupied Austria was after World War II divided into military occupation zones.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria was governed by the Allied Commission for Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As stipulated in the Moscow Declaration of 1943 a subtle difference was seen in the treatment of Austria by the Allies.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian government, consisting of Social Democrats, Conservatives, and Communists resided in Vienna, which was surrounded by the Soviet zone.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This Austrian government was recognised by the allies of World War II in October 1945 despite concerns that Karl Renner could be Stalin's puppet.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 26 July 1946 the Austrian Parliament passed its first nationalization law and approximately 70 mining and manufacturing companies were seized by the Austrian state.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Ministry of Property Protection and Economic Planning (*Ministerium für Vermögenssicherung und Wirtschaftsplanung*) was responsible for directing the nationalized industries under the directorship of Minister Peter Krauland (party ÖVP).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 15 May 1955, after talks which lasted for years and were influenced by the Cold War Austria regained full independence by concluding the Austrian State Treaty with the allies of World War II.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 26 October 1955, all occupation troops had left and Austria declared its *permanent neutrality* by an act of parliament.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This day is now Austria's National Day, a public holiday.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The status of Tyrol was a lingering problem between Austria and Italy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] To this day, there are 20 different squares in Austrian cities called "Südtiroler Platz" (South Tyrolean Square) in memory of the supposed loss of the Austrian territories.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Terrorist acts by the South Tyrolean independence movement have been documented in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] A great degree of autonomy was granted to Tyrol by the Italian national government.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The political system of the Second Republic is based on the constitution of 1920 and 1929, which was reintroduced in 1945.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The system came to be characterised by *Proporz*, whereby most posts of political importance were split proportionately between members of the Social Democratic Party of Austria (SPÖ) and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Interest group "chambers" with mandatory membership (e.g. for workers, business people, farmers) grew to considerable importance and were usually consulted in the legislative process, so hardly any legislation was passed that did not reflect widespread consensus.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Since 1945, governing via a single-party government has occurred twice: 1966–1970 (ÖVP) and 1970–1983 (SPÖ).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] During all other legislative periods, either a grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP or a "small coalition" (one of these two and a smaller party) ruled the country.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Kurt Waldheim, the former secretary-general of the United Nations, was elected President of Austria from 1986 to 1992.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He had been a Wehrmacht officer in the Second World War and was accused of war crimes.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Following a referendum in 1994, at which consent reached a majority of two-thirds, the country became a member of the European Union on 1 January 1995.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In reality, Austria is taking part in the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy, participates in peacekeeping and peace creating tasks, and has become a member of NATO's "Partnership for Peace"; the constitution has been amended accordingly.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Since Liechtenstein joined the Schengen Area in 2011, none of Austria's neighbouring countries performs border controls towards it anymore.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria is a largely mountainous country because of its location in the Alps.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Central Eastern Alps, Northern Limestone Alps, and Southern Limestone Alps are all partly in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Of the total area of Austria (83,871 km2 or 32,383 sq mi), only about a quarter can be considered low-lying, and only 32% of the country is below 500 metres (1,640 ft).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Alps of western Austria give way somewhat into low lands and plains in the eastern part of the country.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria lies between latitudes 46° and 49° N, and longitudes 9° and 18° E.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] It can be divided into five areas, the biggest being the Eastern Alps, which constitute 62% of the nation's total area.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian foothills at the base of the Alps and the Carpathians account for about 12% and the foothills in the east and areas surrounding the periphery of the Pannoni low country amount to about 12% of the total landmass.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The second greater mountain area (much lower than the Alps) is situated in the north.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Known as the Austrian granite plateau, it is located in the central area of the Bohemian Mass and accounts for 10% of Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian portion of the Vienna basin makes up the remaining 4%.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In Austria, forest cover is about 47% of the total land area, equivalent to 3,899,150 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 3,775,670 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 2,227,500 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 1,671,500 hectares (ha).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 2% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and about 23% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] For the year 2015, 18% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 82% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Phytogeographically, Austria belongs to the Central European province of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] According to the WWF, the territory of Austria can be subdivided into four ecoregions: the Central European mixed forests, Pannonian mixed forests, Alps conifer and mixed forests, and Western European broadleaf forests.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 3.55/10, ranking it 149th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The greater part of Austria lies in the cool/temperate climate zone, where humid westerly winds predominate.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] With nearly three-quarters of the country dominated by the Alps, the alpine climate is predominant.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In the east—in the Pannonian Plain and along the Danube valley—the climate shows continental features with less rain than the alpine areas.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Although Austria is cold in the winter (−10 to 0 °C), summer temperatures can be relatively high, with average temperatures in the mid-20s and a highest temperature of 40.5 °C (105 °F) in August 2013.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification Austria has the following climate types: humid subtropical (Cfa), oceanic (Cfb), cool/warm-summer humid continental (Dfb), subarctic/subalpine (Dfc), tundra/alpine (ET), and ice-cap (EF).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria may experience very cold, severe winters, but most of the time they are only around as cold as those in somewhat comparable climate zones, for example, Southern Scandinavia or Eastern Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As well, at higher altitudes, summers are usually considerably cooler than in the valleys/lower altitudes.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The subarctic and tundra climates seen around the Alps are much warmer in winter than what is normal elsewhere due in part to the Oceanic influence on this part of Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Climate change in Austria has already caused temperature rises of almost 2 °C since 1880, and temperatures are expected to increase further while heat waves become more common.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Extreme precipitation events have become more frequent, and associated floods and landslides could threaten Austria's electricity supply security.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria's mountainous regions are highly sensitive to climate change and are experiencing reduced snowfall, earlier snowmelt and glacier loss.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Parliament of Austria is located in Vienna, the country's capital and most populous city.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria became a federal, representative democratic republic through the Federal Constitutional Law of 1920.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The political system of the Second Republic with its nine states is based on the constitution of 1920, amended in 1929, which was re-enacted on 1 May 1945.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The president of Austria is the head of state.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The president is directly elected by popular majority vote, with a run-off between the top-scoring candidates if necessary.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The chancellor of Austria is head of the government.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The chancellor is selected by the president and tasked with forming a government based on the partisan composition of the lower house of parliament.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The government can be removed from office by either a presidential decree or by vote of no confidence in the lower chamber of parliament, the *Nationalrat*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Voting for the president and for the parliament used to be compulsory in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The compulsion was abolished in steps from 1982 to 2004.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria's parliament consists of two chambers.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The voting age was lowered from 18 to 16 in 2007.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] While there is a general threshold of 4% of the vote for all parties in federal elections (*Nationalratswahlen*) to participate in the proportional allocation of seats, there remains the possibility of being elected to a seat directly in one of the 43 regional electoral districts (*Direktmandat*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Nationalrat is the dominant chamber in the legislative process in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] However, the upper house of parliament, the *Bundesrat*, has a limited right of veto (the Nationalrat can—in almost all cases—ultimately pass the respective bill by voting a second time; this is referred to as a *Beharrungsbeschluss*, lit.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] A constitutional convention, called the *Österreich -Konvent* was convened on 30 June 2003 to consider reforms to the constitution, but failed to produce a proposal that would command a two-thirds majority in the Nationalrat, the margin necessary for constitutional amendments or reforms.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] While the bicameral Parliament and the Government constitute the legislative and executive branches, respectively, the courts are the third branch of Austrian state powers.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Constitutional Court exerts considerable influence on the political system because of its power to invalidate legislation and ordinances that are not in compliance with the Constitution.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Since 1995, the European Court of Justice may overrule Austrian decisions in all matters defined in the laws of the European Union.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria also implements the decisions of the European Court of Human Rights, since the European Convention on Human Rights is part of the Austrian constitution.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] After the general election held in October 2006, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) emerged as the strongest party, and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) came in second, having lost about 8 Percentage points of its previous polling.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Political realities prohibited any of the two major parties from forming a coalition with smaller parties.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In January 2007 the ÖVP and SPÖ formed a grand coalition with Alfred Gusenbauer (SPÖ) as Chancellor.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The election in September 2008 further weakened both major parties (SPÖ 29.3 % and ÖVP 26.0 %).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] They formed a coalition with Werner Faymann (SPÖ) as Chancellor (First Faymann government).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Green Party came in third with 11% of the vote.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The FPÖ and the deceased Jörg Haider's new party Alliance for the Future of Austria, both on the political right, were strengthened during the election but taken together received less than 20% of the vote.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 11 October 2008, Jörg Haider died in a car accident.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In the legislative elections of 2013, the Social Democratic Party received 27% of the vote and 52 seats; the People's Party 24% and 47 seats, thus controlling together the majority of the seats.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Freedom Party received 40 seats and 21% of the votes, while the Greens received 12% and 24 seats.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Two new parties, Stronach and the NEOS, received less than 10% of the vote, and 11 and nine seats respectively.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 17 May 2016, Christian Kern from Social Democrats (SPÖ) was sworn in as the new chancellor.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He continued governing in a "grand coalition" with the conservative People's Party (ÖVP).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He took the office after the former chancellor, also from SPÖ, Werner Faymann's resignation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 26 January 2017, Alexander Van der Bellen was sworn in as the mostly ceremonial – but symbolically significant – role of Austrian president.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] After the Grand Coalition broke in Spring 2017 a snap election was proclaimed for October 2017.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) with its new young leader Sebastian Kurz emerged as the largest party in the National Council, winning 31.5% of votes and 62 of the 183 seats.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) finished second with 52 seats and 26.9% votes, slightly ahead of the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ), which received 51 seats and 26 percent.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The ÖVP decided to form a coalition with the FPÖ.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The new government between the centre-right wing and the right-wing populist party under the new chancellor Sebastian Kurz was sworn in on 18 December 2017, but the coalition government later collapsed in the wake of the "Ibiza" corruption scandal and new elections were called for 29 September 2019.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The elections led to another landslide victory (37.5 percent) of the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) which formed a coalition government with the reinvigorated (13.9 percent) Greens, which was sworn in with Kurz as chancellor on 7 January 2020.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 11 October 2021, Chancellor Sebastian Kurz resigned following pressure from a corruption scandal.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] He was succeeded by Foreign Minister Alexander Schallenberg of the ÖVP.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] However, Schallenberg stepped down after less than two months, and Karl Nehammer was sworn in as chancellor on 6 December 2021, making him Austria's third conservative leader in two months.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The ÖVP and the Greens continued to govern together.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Following the election on 29 September 2024, coalition negotiations between the ÖVP, SPÖ, and NEOS collapsed, leading to Nehammer's resignation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Schallenberg stepped in as interim chancellor for the second time.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Attempts to form an ÖVP-FPÖ coalition also failed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Eventually, the ÖVP, SPÖ, and NEOS reached an agreement, forming a coalition government with Christian Stocker (ÖVP) as chancellor (Stocker government).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria is a federal republic consisting of nine states (Austrian German: *Bundesländer*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The states are sub-divided into districts (*Bezirke*) and statutory cities (*Statutarstädte*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Districts are subdivided into municipalities (*Gemeinden*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Statutory Cities have the competencies otherwise granted to both districts and municipalities.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Vienna is unique in that it is both a city and a state.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The European Commission's Directorate-General for Translation calls the states *provinces*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The 1955 Austrian State Treaty ended the occupation of Austria following World War II and recognised Austria as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] On 26 October 1955, the Federal Assembly passed a constitutional article in which "Austria declares of her own free will her perpetual neutrality".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The second section of this law stated that "in all future times Austria will not join any military alliances and will not permit the establishment of any foreign military bases on her territory".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Since then, Austria has shaped its foreign policy on the basis of neutrality, but rather different from the neutrality of Switzerland.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria began to reassess its definition of neutrality following the fall of the Soviet Union, granting overflight rights for the UN-sanctioned action against Iraq in 1991, and since 1995, it has developed participation in the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Also in 1995, it joined NATO's Partnership for Peace (although it was careful to do so only after Russia joined) and subsequently participated in peacekeeping missions in Bosnia.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Meanwhile, the only part of the Constitutional Law on Neutrality of 1955 still fully valid is not to allow foreign military bases in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria signed the UN's Nuclear Weapon Ban Treaty, which was opposed by all NATO members.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The manpower of the Austrian Armed Forces (Austrian German: *Bundesheer*) mainly relies on conscription.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] All males who have reached the age of eighteen and are found fit have to serve a six months compulsory military service, followed by an eight-year reserve obligation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Both males and females at the age of sixteen are eligible for voluntary service.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Conscientious objection is legally acceptable and those who claim this right are obliged to serve an institutionalised nine months civilian service instead.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Since 1998, women volunteers have been allowed to become professional soldiers.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Austria is a landlocked country and has no navy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In 2012, Austria's defence expenditures corresponded to approximately 0.8% of its GDP.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Army currently has about 26,000 soldiers, of whom about 12,000 are conscripts.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] As head of state, the Austrian president is nominally the commander-in-chief of the Armed Forces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Command of the Austrian Armed Forces is exercised by the minister of defence, as of May 2020: Klaudia Tanner.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] This assistance came to an end when Hungary and Slovakia joined the EU Schengen Area in 2008, for all intents and purposes abolishing "internal" border controls between treaty states.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Some politicians have called for a prolongation of this mission, but the legality of this is heavily disputed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] In accordance with the Austrian constitution, armed forces may only be deployed in a limited number of cases, mainly to defend the country and aid in cases of national emergency, such as in the wake of natural disasters.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] They may only exceptionally be used as auxiliary police forces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Within its self-declared status of permanent neutrality, Austria has a tradition of engaging in UN-led peacekeeping and other humanitarian missions.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] The Austrian Forces Disaster Relief Unit (AFDRU), in particular, an all-volunteer unit with close ties to civilian specialists (e.g. rescue dog handlers) enjoys a reputation as a quick (standard deployment time is 10 hours) and efficient SAR unit.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] Currently, larger contingents of Austrian forces are deployed in Bosnia and Kosovo.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Austria is the 3rd most peaceful country in the world.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria consistently ranks high in terms of GDP per capita, due to its highly industrialised economy, and well-developed social market economy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Until the 1980s, many of Austria's largest industry firms were nationalised; in recent years, however, privatisation has reduced state holdings to a level comparable to other European economies.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Labour movements are particularly influential, exercising a large influence on labour politics and decisions related to the expansion of the economy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Next to a highly developed industry, international tourism is the most important part of the economy of Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Germany has historically been the main trading partner of Austria, making it vulnerable to rapid changes in the German economy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Since Austria became a member state of the European Union, it has gained closer ties to other EU economies.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Membership of the EU has drawn an influx of foreign investors attracted by Austria's access to the single European market and proximity to the aspiring economies of the European Union.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] At least 67% of Austria's imports come from other European Union member states.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The 2008 financial crisis led to the Hypo Alpe-Adria-Bank International to be purchased in December 2009 by the government for 1 euro owing to credit difficulties, thus wiping out the €1.63bn of BayernLB.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] As of February 2014, the HGAA situation was unresolved, causing Chancellor Werner Faymann to warn that its failure would be comparable to the 1931 Creditanstalt event.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria indicated on 16 November 2010 that it would withhold the December instalment of its contribution to the EU bailout of Greece, citing the material worsening of the Greek debt situation and the apparent inability of Greece to collect the level of tax receipts it had previously promised.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Since the fall of communism, Austrian companies have been quite active players and consolidators in Eastern Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Between 1995 and 2010, 4,868 mergers and acquisitions with a total known value of 163 billion EUR with the involvement of Austrian firms have been announced.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Tourism in Austria accounts for almost 9% of its gross domestic product.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 2007, Austria ranked 9th worldwide in international tourism receipts, with 18.9 billion US$.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In international tourist arrivals, Austria ranked 12th with 20.8 million tourists.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 1972 the country began construction of a nuclear power plant to produce electricity at Zwentendorf on the River Danube, following a unanimous vote in parliament.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] However, in 1978 a referendum voted approximately 50.5% against nuclear power, 49.5% for, and parliament subsequently unanimously passed a law forbidding the use of nuclear power to generate electricity although the nuclear power plant had already finished.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria currently produces more than half of its electricity by hydropower.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Together with other renewable energy sources such as wind power, solar power, and biomass, the electricity supply from renewable energy amounts to 62.89 percent.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Compared to most European countries, Austria is ecologically well endowed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Its biocapacity (or biological natural capital) is more than double of the world average: In 2016 Austria had 3.8 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, compared to the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] By contrast, in 2016 they used 6.0 global hectares of biocapacity which amounts to Austria's ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] This means that Austrians use about 60% more biocapacity than Austria contains.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] As a result, Austria is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Rail transport in Austria is primarily provided by the national carrier Austrian Federal Railways (*Österreichische Bundesbahnen*, ÖBB).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] It operates most commuter rail systems and long-distance trains.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria's population was estimated to be 9,220,882 in April 2026 by Statistik Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The population of the capital, Vienna, exceeds 2 million, representing about a quarter of the country's population.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] It is known for its cultural offerings and high standard of living.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] All other cities have fewer than 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] According to Statistik Austria, at the beginning of 2024, there were 1.8 million foreign-born residents in Austria, corresponding to 22.3% of the total population.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] There are more than 620,100 descendants of foreign-born immigrants.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] There are a group of legally recognized indigenous non-German speaking minorities, like Carinthian Slovenes, or the approximately 25,000 Romani people.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The total fertility rate (TFR) in 2023 was estimated at 1.32 children born per woman, below the replacement rate of 2.1, it remains considerably below the high of 4.83 children born per woman in 1873.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 2015, 42.1% of births were to unmarried women.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria had the 14th oldest population in the world in 2020, with the average age of 44.5 years.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The life expectancy in 2024 was estimated at 82.3 years, placing Austria above the EU average of 81.7 years.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 2024, Statistik Austria estimated that the population will grow to 10,179,834 people by 2080, primarily driven by immigration.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The official language of Austria is German, as specified by article 8 of its constitution of 1920.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The written form of German in Austria and in the Italian South Tyrol region is Austrian German, or simply Austrian, a variety of Standard High German; it has been standardized in Austria since 1951, when the Ministry of Education, Science and Research published the *Österreichisches Wörterbuch*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] This standard form, however, is used primarily in education and for government publications, announcements and websites; the *de facto* common spoken languages of Austria are not the Austrian German as taught in schools but rather the Bavarian and Alemannic dialects.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] These are two mutually intelligible Upper German local languages or collections of dialects that are understood, with varying degrees of difficulty, by each other as well as by speakers of non-Austrian German dialects.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The Austrian state of Carinthia is home to a significant indigenous Slovene-speaking minority, while in the easternmost state, Burgenland (formerly part of the Hungarian portion of Austria-Hungary), there are significant Hungarian- and Croatian-speaking minorities.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Burgenland Croatian, Hungarian, and Slovene are also recognized as official languages beside German in parts of Carinthia and Burgenland.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] According to census information published by Statistik Austria, there were a total of 710,926 foreign nationals living in Austria in 2001.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Of these, the largest by far were 283,334 foreign nationals from the former Yugoslavia (of whom 135,336 spoke Serbian; 105,487 Croatian; 31,591 Bosnian — i.e., 272,414 Austrian resident native speakers in total, plus 6,902 Slovenian and 4,018 Macedonian speakers).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The predominant historic ethnicity of Austrians is German speaking, which is closely related to people from neighbouring countries Germany, Liechtenstein, and German-speaking Switzerland.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austrian ethnicity has considerable convergence with non-German speaking populations to the east and south of Austria, particularly in Vienna, through its position and role in Eastern Europe today and as the capital of the former multi-ethnic Habsburg Empire.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] This is reflected in the officially recognized non-German speaking indigneous populations of Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] An estimated 13,000 to 40,000 Slovenes in the Austrian state Carinthia (the Carinthian Slovenes) as well as Croats (about 30,000) and Hungarians in Burgenland were recognised as a minority and have had special rights following the Austrian State Treaty (*Staatsvertrag*) of 1955.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Since 1994 the Romani people and Sinti have been an officially recognised ethnic minority in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria's people who are of non-Austrian descent, many come from surrounding countries, especially from the former East Bloc nations.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Guest workers *(Gastarbeiter)* and their descendants, as well as refugees from the Yugoslav wars and other conflicts, also form an important minority group in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The largest single immigrant group in Austria are Germans, only collectively surpassed by people from ex-Jugoslavian countries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The largest group of people born in ex-Jugoslavian countries are from Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The next biggest group are people born in Turkey.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] People from Turkey are closely followed by people from Serbia.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Serbs form one of the largest ethnic groups in Austria, numbering around 300,000 people.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Historically, Serbian immigrants moved to Austria during the time of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, when Vojvodina was under Imperial control.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Following World War II the number of Serbs expanded again, and today the community is very large.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The Austrian Serbian Society was founded in 1936.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Today, Serbs in Austria are mainly found in Vienna, Salzburg, and Graz.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria was historically a strongly Catholic country as the centre of the Habsburg monarchy, which championed Catholicism.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 2001, about 74% of Austria's population were registered as Catholic, while about 5% considered themselves Protestants.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austrian Christians, both Catholic and Protestant, are obliged to pay a mandatory membership fee (calculated by income – about 1%) to their churches; this payment is called the *Kirchenbeitrag* ("ecclesiastical contribution").
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] From the second half of the 20th century, the number of adherents and churchgoers has declined.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Data for 2023 list 4,638,000 members of the Catholic Church, or about 50% of the total Austrian population, yet Sunday church attendance was only 347,000, or 3.7% of the total Austrian population.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Additionally, the Lutheran church recorded a loss of 74,421 adherents between 2001 and 2016.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The 2001 census reported that about 12% of the population declared themselves without a religion; according to ecclesiastical information, this share had grown to 20% by 2015 and further increased to 22.4% (1,997,700 people) in 2021.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Of the remaining population, about 340,000 were registered as members of various Muslim communities in 2001, originating chiefly from Turkey, Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Kosovo; the number of Muslims doubled in the fifteen years to 2016, to 700,000, and reached 745,600 in 2021.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 2021, another 436,700 residents of Austria (mostly Serbs) were members of Eastern Orthodox Churches, 26,600 were Buddhists, 10,100 were Hindus, about 21,800 were active Jehovah's Witnesses, and 5,400 were Jews.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Education in Austria is federally governed by the Ministry of Education, Science and Research, with administration handled by individual states.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] School attendance is mandatory for nine years, typically from ages six to fifteen.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Kindergarten is available for children aged three to six, with compulsory attendance starting at five.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] While part-time daycare is free nationwide for this age group, Vienna and Burgenland offer free all-day care.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] By 2018, about 90% of children between three and five attended early childhood education.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Volksschule or Grundschule starts at age six and lasts for four years, with an average class size of 18 pupils.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Secondary education is divided into different tracks: Mittelschule, which focuses on vocational training, and Allgemeinbildende Höhere Schule, an academic secondary school that prepares students for university through the Matura examination.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] At age 10, students, parents, and teachers decide the most suitable path based on the child's abilities and interests.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria is also known for its dual education system, which integrates theoretical learning with practical training; in 2021, 34.1% of secondary level II students participated in this system.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria allocated 4.9% of its GDP to education in 2021, with spending per student averaging US$16,734.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] German proficiency is essential in public schools, and children's language skills are assessed using the MIKA-D test upon admission.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Students who require additional support receive targeted language assistance to facilitate integration into the educational system.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Even though Austria has a 0.9 health index and a life expectancy of 81 years, the country still faces numerous problems when it comes to health, one example being that 2 in 5 Austrians have a chronic condition.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] One of the most costly health services in the EU is located in Austria.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In 2019, health spending per capita ranked third in the EU.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Health-related out-of-pocket expenditures are higher than the EU average.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] With 5.2 physicians per 1,000 inhabitants, Austria has among the highest physician density in OECD countries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Overall, the country has 271 hospitals with a total of 45,596 physicians (data from 2017), about 54% of which work (also or primarily) in hospitals.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Although Austria has the second highest physician rate in the EU, a large share of physicians is tropical to retirement age (55 years and older), and may thus be at a higher risk of developing severe conditions in a specimen of COVID-19 infection.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The number of nurses in Austria has been subject to debate in recent years with regard to definitions of qualifications and their interpretation in cross-country comparisons.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] A new mandatory health professional registry was set up in 2018.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] However, due to the elapsing of the COVID-19 pandemic in early 2020, compulsory registration has been suspended.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] This implies that professional activities in long-term superintendency are moreover possible without registration until the end of the pandemic by late spring 2022 (Transition without the pandemic is still to be defined).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria's past as a European power and its cultural environment generated a broad contribution to various forms of art, most notably among them music.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria was the birthplace of many famous composers such as Joseph Haydn, Michael Haydn, Franz Liszt, Franz Schubert, Anton Bruckner, Johann Strauss Sr., and Johann Strauss Jr., as well as members of the Second Viennese School such as Arnold Schoenberg, Anton Webern, and Alban Berg.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was born in Salzburg, then an independent Church Principality of the Holy Roman Empire, which later became part of Austria, and much of Mozart's career was spent in Vienna.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Vienna was for a long time an important centre of musical innovation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] 18th- and 19th-century composers were drawn to the city due to the patronage of the Habsburgs, and made Vienna the European capital of classical music.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] During the Baroque period, Slavic and Hungarian folk forms influenced Austrian music.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Vienna's status began its rise as a cultural centre in the early 16th century and was focused around instruments, including the lute.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Ludwig van Beethoven spent the better part of his life in Vienna.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria's current national anthem, attributed to Mozart, was chosen after World War II to replace the traditional Austrian anthem by Joseph Haydn.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austrian Herbert von Karajan was principal conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic for 35 years.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] He is generally regarded as one of the greatest conductors of the 20th century, and he was a dominant figure in European classical music from the 1960s until his death.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria was the cradle of numerous scientists with international reputation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Among them are Ludwig Boltzmann, Ernst Mach, Victor Franz Hess, and Christian Doppler, prominent scientists in the 19th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In the 20th century, contributions by Lise Meitner, Erwin Schrödinger, and Wolfgang Pauli to nuclear research and quantum mechanics were key to these areas' development during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Prominent present-day quantum physicists are Anton Zeilinger and Peter Zoller renown for important developments in quantum optics and quantum information.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In addition to physicists, Austria was the birthplace of two of the most noteworthy philosophers of the 20th century, Ludwig Wittgenstein and Karl Popper.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In addition to them, biologists Gregor Mendel and Konrad Lorenz as well as mathematician Kurt Gödel and engineers such as Ferdinand Porsche and Siegfried Marcus were Austrians.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Bertha von Suttner became the first woman to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, and the first Austrian laureate.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] A focus of Austrian science has always been medicine and psychology, starting in medieval times with Paracelsus.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Eminent physicians like Theodore Billroth, Clemens von Pirquet, and Anton von Eiselsberg have built upon the achievements of the 19th-century Vienna School of Medicine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria was home to Sigmund Freud, founder of psychoanalysis, Alfred Adler, founder of Individual psychology, psychologists Paul Watzlawick and Hans Asperger, and psychiatrist Viktor Frankl.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria was ranked 17th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, but it declined to the 19th rank according to GII 2025.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The Austrian School of Economics, which is prominent as one of the main competitive directions for economic theory, is related to Austrian economists Carl Menger, Joseph Schumpeter, Eugen von Böhm-Bawerk, Ludwig von Mises, and Friedrich Hayek.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Other noteworthy Austrian-born émigrés include the econimic anthropologist Karl Paul Polanyi, management thinker Peter Drucker, sociologist Paul Felix Lazarsfeld, and scientist Sir Gustav Nossal.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria's cuisine is derived from that of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austrian cuisine is rooted in the long-standing traditions of the imperial court kitchen ("Hofküche"), which evolved over centuries within the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] It is distinguished by its refined and well-balanced preparation of beef and pork, as well as by a wide variety of vegetable-based dishes.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In addition to native regional traditions, the cuisine has been influenced by Hungarian, Czech, Polish, Jewish, Italian, Balkan, and French cuisines, from which both dishes and methods of food preparation have often been borrowed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The Austrian cuisine is therefore one of the most multicultural and transcultural in Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Typical Austrian dishes include Wiener Schnitzel, Schweinsbraten, Kaiserschmarren, Knödel, Sachertorte, and Tafelspitz.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] There are also Kärntner Kasnudeln, which are pockets of dough filled with Topfen, potatoes, herbs and peppermint which are boiled and served with a butter sauce.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Kasnudeln are traditionally served with a salad.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The sugar block dispenser Pez was invented in Austria, as well as Mannerschnitten.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria is also famous for its Mozartkugeln and its coffee tradition.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] With over 8 kg per year it has the sixth highest per capita coffee consumption worldwide.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Beer is sold in 0.2-litre (a *Pfiff*), 0.3-litre (a *Seidel*, *kleines Bier* or *Glas Bier*) and 0.5-litre (a *Krügerl* or *großes Bier* or *Halbe*) measures.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] At festivals one litre *Maß* and two-litre *Doppelmaß* in the Bavarian style are also dispensed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The most popular types of beer are lager (known as *Märzen* in Austria), naturally cloudy *Zwicklbier* and wheat beer.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] At holidays like Christmas and Easter bock beer is also available.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The most important wine-producing areas are in Lower Austria, Burgenland, Styria, and Vienna.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The Grüner Veltliner grape provides some of Austria's most notable white wines and Zweigelt is the most widely planted red wine grape.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] In Upper Austria, Lower Austria, Styria, and Carinthia, *Most*, a type of cider or perry, is widely produced.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] A Schnapps of typically up to 60% alcohol or fruit brandy is drunk, which in Austria is made from a variety of fruits, for example apricots and rowanberries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The produce of small private schnapps distilleries, of which there are about 20,000 in Austria, is known as *Selbstgebrannter* or *Hausbrand*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Local soft drinks such as Almdudler are very popular around the country as an alternative to alcoholic beverages.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Another popular drink is the so-called "Spezi", a mix between Coca-Cola and the original formula of Orange Fanta or the more locally renowned Frucade.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Red Bull, the highest-selling energy drink in the world, was introduced by Dietrich Mateschitz, an Austrian entrepreneur.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Due to the mountainous terrain, alpine skiing is a prominent sport in Austria and is extremely valuable in the promotion and economic growth of the country.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Similar sports such as snowboarding or ski-jumping are also widely popular.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton are also popular events with a permanent track located in Igls, which hosted bobsleigh and luge competitions for the 1964 and 1976 Winter Olympics held in Innsbruck.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The first Winter Youth Olympics in 2012 were held in Innsbruck as well.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Football in Austria is governed by the Austrian Football Association.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria was among the most successful football playing nations on the European continent, placing 4th at the 1934 FIFA World Cup, 3rd at the 1954 FIFA World Cup and 7th at the 1978 FIFA World Cup.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] However, Austrian football has not been internationally successful since the mid 20th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria co-hosted the 2008 UEFA European Football Championship with Switzerland.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] The national Austrian football league is the Austrian Bundesliga, which includes teams such as record-champions SK Rapid Wien, FK Austria Wien, Red Bull Salzburg, and Sturm Graz.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Besides football, Austria also has professional national leagues for most major team sports, including the Austrian Hockey League for ice hockey, Österreichische Basketball Bundesliga for basketball and the Austrian Football League for American football.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Horseback riding is also popular; the famed Spanish Riding School of Vienna is located in Vienna.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Niki Lauda was a Formula One driver who was three times F1 World Champion, winning in 1975, 1977 and 1984.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] He is currently the only driver to have been champion for both Ferrari and McLaren, the sport's two most successful constructors.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Other known Austrian F1 drivers include Gerhard Berger and Jochen Rindt.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Austria also hosts F1 races (Austrian Grand Prix); now held at the Red Bull Ring, in the past also at the Österreichring and the Zeltweg Airfield.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Thomas Muster is a former tennis player and was one of the world's leading clay court players in the 1990s.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] He won the 1995 French Open and in 1996 was ranked number 1 in the ATP ranking.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] 2020 US Open winner Dominic Thiem is also another prominent tennis player having been as high as world number 3 and also been in the finals of the French Open and Australian Open.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/austria-p02] Other well known Austrian tennis players include Horst Skoff and Jürgen Melzer.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] A **beam engine** is a type of steam engine where a pivoted overhead beam is used to apply the force from a vertical piston to a vertical connecting rod.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This configuration, with the engine directly driving a pump, was first used by Thomas Newcomen around 1705 to remove water from mines in Cornwall.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The efficiency of the engines was improved by engineers including James Watt, who added a separate condenser; Jonathan Hornblower and Arthur Woolf, who compounded the cylinders; and William McNaught, who devised a method of compounding an existing engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Beam engines were first used to pump water out of mines or into canals but could be used to pump water to supplement the flow for a waterwheel powering a mill.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The **rotative beam engine** is a later design of beam engine where the connecting rod drives a flywheel by means of a crank (or, historically, by means of a sun and planet gear).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] These beam engines could be used to directly power the line-shafting in a mill.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] They also could be used to power steam ships.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The first beam engines were water-powered and used to pump water from mines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] A preserved example may be seen at the Straitsteps Lead Mine in Wanlockhead in Scotland.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Beam engines were extensively used to power pumps on the English canal system when it was expanded by means of locks early in the Industrial Revolution, and also to drain water from mines in the same period, and as winding engines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The first steam-related beam engine was developed by Thomas Newcomen.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This was not, strictly speaking, steam powered, as the steam introduced below the piston was condensed to create a partial vacuum thus allowing atmospheric pressure to push down the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] It was therefore called an Atmospheric Engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The Newcomen atmospheric engine was adopted by many mines in Cornwall and elsewhere, but it was relatively inefficient and consumed a large quantity of fuel.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The engine was improved by John Smeaton but James Watt resolved the main inefficiencies of the Newcomen engine in his Watt steam engine by the addition of a separate condenser, thus allowing the cylinder to remain hot.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Technically this was still an atmospheric engine until (under subsequent patents) he enclosed the upper part of the cylinder, introducing steam to also push the piston down.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This made it a true steam engine and arguably confirms him as the inventor of the steam engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] He also patented the centrifugal governor and the parallel motion. the latter allowed the replacement of chains round an arch head and thus allowed its use as a rotative engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] His patents remained in place until the start of the 19th Century and some say that this held back development.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] However, in reality development had been ongoing by others and at the end of the patent period there was an explosion of new ideas and improvements.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Watt's beam engines were used commercially in much larger numbers and many continued to run for 100 years or more.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Watt held patents on key aspects of his engine's design, but his rotative engine was equally restricted by James Pickard's patent of the simple crank.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The beam engine went on to be considerably improved and enlarged in the tin- and copper-rich areas of south west England, which enabled the draining of the deep mines that existed there.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Consequently, the Cornish beam engines became world-famous, as they remain among the most massive beam engines ever constructed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Because of the number of patents on various parts of the engines and the consequences of patent infringements, examples exist of Beam Engines with no makers name on any of the parts (Hollycombe Steam Collection).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] In a rotative beam engine, the piston is mounted vertically, and the piston rod drives the beam as before.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] A connecting rod from the other end of the beam, rather than driving a pump rod, now drives a flywheel.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Early Watt engines used Watt's patent sun and planet gear, rather than a simple crank, as use of the latter was protected by a patent owned by James Pickard.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Once the patent had expired, the simple crank was employed universally.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Once rotary motion had been achieved a drive belt could be attached beside the flywheel.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This transmitted the power to other drive shafts and from these other belts could then be attached to power a variety of static machinery e.g. threshing, grinding or milling machines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The first steam-powered ships used variants of the rotative beam engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] These marine steam engines – known as side-lever, grasshopper, crosshead, or 'walking beam', among others – all varied from the original land-based machines by locating the beam or beams in different positions to take up less room on board ship.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Compounding involves two or more cylinders; low-pressure steam from the first, high-pressure, cylinder is passed to the second cylinder where it expands further and provides more drive.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This is the compound effect; the waste steam from this can produce further work if it is then passed into a condenser in the normal way.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The first experiment with compounding was conducted by Jonathan Hornblower, who took out a patent in 1781.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] His first engine was installed at Tincroft Mine, Cornwall.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] It had two cylinders – one 21-inch (0.53 m) diameter with 6-foot (1.8 m) stroke and one 27-inch (0.69 m) diameter with 8-foot (2.4 m) stroke – placed alongside each other at one end of the beam.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The early engines showed little performance gain: the steam pressure was too low, interconnecting pipes were of small diameter and the condenser ineffective.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] At this time the laws of thermodynamics were not adequately understood, particularly the concept of absolute zero.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Engineers such as Arthur Woolf were trying to tackle an engineering problem with an imperfect understanding of the physics.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] In particular, their valve gear was cutting-in at the wrong position in the stroke, not allowing for expansive working in the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] Successful Woolf compound engines were produced in 1814, for the Wheal Abraham copper mine and the Wheal Vor tin mine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] William McNaught patented a compound beam engine in 1845.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] On a beam engine of the standard Boulton & Watt design he placed a high-pressure cylinder, on the opposite side of the beam to the existing single cylinder, where the water pump was normally fitted.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This had two important effects: it massively reduced the pressure on the beam, and the connecting steam pipe, being long, acted as an expansive receiver – the element missing in the Woolf design.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] This modification could be made retrospectively, and engines so modified were said to be "McNaughted".
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/beam-engine] The advantages of a compound engine were not significant at pressures under 60 pounds per square inch (410 kPa), but showed at over 100 psi (690 kPa).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] A **blast furnace** is a type of metallurgical furnace used for smelting to produce industrial metals, generally pig iron, but also others such as lead or copper.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] *Blast* refers to the combustion air being supplied above atmospheric pressure.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The end products are usually molten metal and slag phases tapped from the bottom, and flue gases exiting from the top.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The downward flow of the ore along with the flux in contact with an upflow of hot, carbon monoxide-rich combustion gases is a countercurrent exchange and chemical reaction process.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In contrast, air furnaces (such as reverberatory furnaces) are naturally aspirated, usually by the convection of hot gases in a chimney flue.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] According to this broad definition, bloomeries for iron, blowing houses for tin, and smelt mills for lead would be classified as blast furnaces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] However, the term has usually been limited to those used for smelting iron ore to produce pig iron, an intermediate material used in the production of commercial iron and steel, and the shaft furnaces used in combination with sinter plants in base metals smelting.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Blast furnaces are estimated to have been responsible for over 4% of global greenhouse gas emissions between 1900 and 2015, and are difficult to decarbonize.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Blast furnaces operate on the principle of chemical reduction whereby carbon monoxide converts iron oxides to elemental iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Blast furnaces differ from bloomeries and reverberatory furnaces in that in a blast furnace, flue gas is in direct contact with the ore and iron, allowing carbon monoxide to diffuse into the ore and reduce the iron oxide.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The blast furnace operates as a countercurrent exchange process whereas a bloomery does not.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Another difference is that bloomeries operate as a batch process whereas blast furnaces operate continuously for long periods.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Continuous operation is also preferred because blast furnaces are difficult to start and stop.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Also, the carbon in pig iron lowers the melting point below that of steel or pure iron; in contrast, iron does not melt in a bloomery.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Silica has to be removed from the pig iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] It reacts with calcium oxide (burned limestone) and forms silicates, which float to the surface of the molten pig iron as slag.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Historically, iron was produced with charcoal to prevent sulfur contamination.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In a blast furnace, a downward-moving column of ore, flux, coke (or charcoal) and their reaction products must be sufficiently porous for the flue gas to pass through, upwards.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] To ensure this permeability the particle size of the coke or charcoal is of great relevance.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Therefore, the coke must be strong enough so it will not be crushed by the weight of the material above it.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Besides the physical strength of its particles, the coke must also be low in sulfur, phosphorus, and ash.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Hot carbon monoxide is the reducing agent for the iron ore and reacts with the iron oxide to produce molten iron and carbon dioxide.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Depending on the temperature in the different parts of the furnace (warmest at the bottom) the iron is reduced in several steps.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] At the top, where the temperature usually is in the range between 200 and 700 °C (392 and 1,292 °F), the iron oxide is partially reduced to iron(II,III) oxide, Fe3O4.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Hot carbon dioxide, unreacted carbon monoxide, and nitrogen from the air pass up through the furnace as fresh feed material travels down into the reaction zone.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The pig iron produced by the blast furnace has a relatively high carbon content of around 4–5% and usually contains too much sulphur, making it very brittle, and of limited immediate commercial use.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Some pig iron is used to make cast iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The majority of pig iron produced by blast furnaces undergoes further processing to reduce the carbon and sulphur content and produce various grades of steel used for construction materials, automobiles, ships and machinery.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Desulphurisation usually takes place during the transport of the liquid steel to the steelworks.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This is done by adding *calcium oxide*, which reacts with the iron sulfide contained in the pig iron to form calcium sulfide (called *lime desulfurization*).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In a further process step, the so-called basic oxygen steelmaking, the carbon is oxidized by blowing oxygen onto the liquid pig iron to form *crude steel*.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Cast iron has been found in China dating to the 5th century BC, but the earliest extant blast furnaces in China date to the 1st century AD and in the West from the High Middle Ages.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] They spread from the region around Namur in Wallonia (Belgium) in the late 15th century, being introduced to England in 1491.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The fuel used in these was invariably charcoal.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The successful substitution of coke for charcoal is widely attributed to British inventor Abraham Darby in 1709.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The efficiency of the process was further enhanced by the practice of preheating the combustion air (hot blast), patented by British inventor James Beaumont Neilson in 1828.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Archaeological evidence shows that iron-smelting techniques and bloomeries were brought to China by nomadic peoples around 800 BC.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Wrought iron artifacts were originally only found in the northwest, but by the 6th century BC, luxury items such as wrought iron swords and knives were widespread in China.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Bloomery iron co-existed with blast furnaces and cast iron, which were invented shortly after wrought iron technology entered China, for quite some time.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Cast iron pieces have been found alongside wrought iron in Shanxi Province dating to the 9th-8th centuries BC, however it is uncertain if these cast iron pieces were accidental byproducts of the iron smelting process.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Adzes made using cast iron with a decarburised layer of steel have been found in Luoyang dating to the 5th century BC.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Cast iron farming tools that had undergone an annealing process to decrease brittleness were found in burials and smelting cites dating to the 4th century BC.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Bloomery iron disappeared in China after the 3rd century AD with the exception of Xinjiang, where bloomery iron objects could be found as late as the 9th century AD.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In China, blast furnaces produced cast iron, which was then either converted into finished implements in a cupola furnace, or turned into wrought iron in a fining hearth.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Although cast iron farm tools and weapons were widespread in China by the 5th century BC, employing workforces of over 200 men in iron smelters from the 3rd century onward, the earliest blast furnaces constructed were attributed to the Han dynasty in the 1st century AD.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] These early furnaces had clay walls and used phosphorus-containing minerals as a flux.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Chinese blast furnaces ranged from around two to ten meters in height, depending on the region.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The largest ones were found in modern Sichuan and Guangdong, while the 'dwarf" blast furnaces were found in Dabieshan.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In construction, they are both around the same level of technological sophistication.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The effectiveness of the Chinese human and horse powered blast furnaces was enhanced during this period by the engineer Du Shi (c.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] AD 31), who applied the power of waterwheels to piston-bellows in forging cast iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Early water-driven reciprocators for operating blast furnaces were built according to the structure of horse powered reciprocators that already existed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] That is, the circular motion of the wheel, be it horse driven or water driven, was transferred by the combination of a belt drive, a crank-and-connecting-rod, other connecting rods, and various shafts, into the reciprocal motion necessary to operate push bellows.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Donald Wagner suggests that early blast furnace and cast iron production evolved from furnaces used to melt bronze.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Certainly, though, iron was essential to military success by the time the State of Qin had unified China (221 BC).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Usage of the blast and cupola furnace remained widespread during the Song and Tang dynasties.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] By the 11th century, the Song dynasty Chinese iron industry made a switch of resources from charcoal to coke in casting iron and steel, sparing thousands of acres of woodland from felling.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This may have happened as early as the 4th century AD.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The primary advantage of the early blast furnace was in large scale production and making iron implements more readily available to peasants.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Cast iron is more brittle than wrought iron or steel, which required additional fining and then cementation or co-fusion to produce, but for menial activities such as farming it sufficed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] By using the blast furnace, it was possible to produce larger quantities of tools such as ploughshares more efficiently than the bloomery.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In areas where quality was important, such as warfare, wrought iron and steel were preferred.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Nearly all Han period weapons are made of wrought iron or steel, with the exception of axe-heads, of which many are made of cast iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Blast furnaces were also later used to produce gunpowder weapons such as cast iron bomb shells and cast iron cannons during the Song dynasty.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Metalworking is thought to have taken place in Meroë, probably through bloomeries and blast furnaces the earliest use of which in Africa, Meroe, the ancient capital of the Kingdom of Kush in modern-day Sudan, was one of the largest and most influential iron-producing centers in sub-Saharan Africa..
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The simplest forge, known as the Corsican.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Examples of improved bloomeries are the Stuckofen, sometimes called wolf-furnace, which remained until the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Instead of using natural draught, air was pumped in by a *trompe*, resulting in better quality iron and an increased capacity.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This pumping of air in with bellows is known as *cold blast*, and it increases the fuel efficiency of the bloomery and improves yield.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] They can also be built bigger than natural draught bloomeries.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The oldest known blast furnaces in the West were built in Durstel in Switzerland, the Märkische Sauerland in Germany, and at Lapphyttan in Sweden, where the complex was active between 1205 and 1300.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] At Noraskog in the Swedish parish of Järnboås, traces of even earlier blast furnaces have been found, possibly from around 1100.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] These early blast furnaces, like the Chinese examples, were very inefficient compared to those used today.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The iron from the Lapphyttan complex was used to produce balls of wrought iron known as osmonds, and these were traded internationally – a possible reference occurs in a treaty with Novgorod from 1203 and several certain references in accounts of English customs from the 1250s and 1320s.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Other furnaces of the 13th to 15th centuries have been identified in Westphalia.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The technology required for blast furnaces may have either been transferred from China, or may have been an indigenous innovation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Al-Qazvini in the 13th century and other travellers subsequently noted an iron industry in the Alburz Mountains to the south of the Caspian Sea.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This is close to the silk route, so that the use of technology derived from China is conceivable.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Much later descriptions record blast furnaces about three metres high.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] As the Varangian Rus' people from Scandinavia traded with the Caspian (using their Volga trade route), it is possible that the technology reached Sweden by this means.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The Vikings are known to have used double bellows, which greatly increases the volumetric flow of the blast.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The Caspian region may also have been the source for the design of the furnace at Ferriere, described by Filarete, involving a water-powered bellows at Semogo in Valdidentro in northern Italy in 1226.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In a two-stage process the molten iron was tapped twice a day into water, thereby granulating it.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The General Chapter of the Cistercian monks spread some technological advances across Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This may have included the blast furnace, as the Cistercians are known to have been skilled metallurgists.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The Cistercians became the leading iron producers in Champagne, France, from the mid-13th century to the 17th century, also using the phosphate-rich slag from their furnaces as an agricultural fertilizer.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Archaeologists are still discovering the extent of Cistercian technology.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] At Laskill, an outstation of Rievaulx Abbey and the only medieval blast furnace so far identified in Britain, the slag produced was low in iron content.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Slag from other furnaces of the time contained a substantial concentration of iron, whereas Laskill is believed to have produced cast iron quite efficiently.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Its date is not yet clear, but it probably did not survive until Henry VIII's Dissolution of the Monasteries in the late 1530s, as an agreement (immediately after that) concerning the "smythes" with the Earl of Rutland in 1541 refers to blooms.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Nevertheless, the means by which the blast furnace spread in medieval Europe has not finally been determined.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Due to the increased demand for iron for casting cannons, the blast furnace came into widespread use in France in the mid 15th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The direct ancestor of those used in France and England was in the Namur region, in what is now Wallonia (Belgium).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] From there, they spread first to the Pays de Bray on the eastern boundary of Normandy and from there to the Weald of Sussex, where the first furnace (called Queenstock) in Buxted was built in about 1491, followed by one at Newbridge in Ashdown Forest in 1496.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] They remained few in number until about 1530 but many were built in the following decades in the Weald, where the iron industry perhaps reached its peak about 1590.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Most of the pig iron from these furnaces was taken to finery forges for the production of bar iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The first British furnaces outside the Weald appeared during the 1550s, and many were built in the remainder of that century and the following ones.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The output of the industry probably peaked about 1620, and was followed by a slow decline until the early 18th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This was apparently because it was more economic to import iron from Sweden and elsewhere than to make it in some more remote British locations.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Charcoal that was economically available to the industry was probably being consumed as fast as the wood to make it grew.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The first blast furnace in Russia opened in 1637 near Tula and was called the Gorodishche Works.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The blast furnace spread from there to central Russia and then finally to the Urals.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In 1709, at Coalbrookdale in Shropshire, England, Abraham Darby began to fuel a blast furnace with coke instead of charcoal.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Coke's initial advantage was its lower cost, mainly because making coke required much less labor than cutting trees and making charcoal, but using coke also overcame localized shortages of wood, especially in Britain and elsewhere in Europe.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Metallurgical grade coke will bear heavier weight than charcoal, allowing larger furnaces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] A disadvantage is that coke contains more impurities than charcoal, with sulfur being especially detrimental to the iron's quality.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Coke's impurities were more of a problem before hot blast reduced the amount of coke required and before furnace temperatures were hot enough to make slag from limestone free flowing.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Coke iron was initially only used for foundry work, making pots and other cast iron goods.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Foundry work was a minor branch of the industry, but Darby's son built a new furnace at nearby Horsehay, and began to supply the owners of finery forges with coke pig iron for the production of bar iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Coke pig iron was by this time cheaper to produce than charcoal pig iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The use of a coal-derived fuel in the iron industry was a key factor in the British Industrial Revolution.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] However, in many areas of the world charcoal was cheaper while coke was more expensive even after the Industrial Revolution: e. g., in the US charcoal-fueled iron production fell in share to about a half c.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] 1850 but still continued to increase in absolute terms until c.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] 1890, while in João Monlevade in the Brazilian Highlands charcoal-fired blast furnaces were built as late as the 1930s and only phased out in 2000.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Darby's original blast furnace has been archaeologically excavated and can be seen in situ at Coalbrookdale, part of the Ironbridge Gorge Museums.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Cast iron from the furnace was used to make girders for the world's first cast iron bridge in 1779.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The Iron Bridge crosses the River Severn at Coalbrookdale and remains in use for pedestrians.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The steam engine was applied to power blast air, overcoming a shortage of water power in areas where coal and iron ore were located.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This was first done at Coalbrookdale where a steam engine replaced a horse-powered pump in 1742.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Such engines were used to pump water to a reservoir above the furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The first engines used to blow cylinders directly was supplied by Boulton and Watt to John Wilkinson's New Willey Furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This powered a cast iron blowing cylinder, which had been invented by his father Isaac Wilkinson.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] He patented such cylinders in 1736, to replace the leather bellows, which wore out quickly.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Isaac was granted a second patent, also for blowing cylinders, in 1757.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The steam engine and cast iron blowing cylinder led to a large increase in British iron production in the late 18th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Hot blast was the single most important advance in fuel efficiency of the blast furnace and was one of the most important technologies developed during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Hot blast was patented by James Beaumont Neilson at Wilsontown Ironworks in Britain in 1828.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Within a few years of the introduction, hot blast was developed to the point where fuel consumption was cut by one-third using coke or two-thirds using coal, while furnace capacity was also significantly increased.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Within a few decades, the practice was to have a "stove" as large as the furnace next to it into which the waste gas (containing CO) from the furnace was directed and burnt.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The resultant heat was used to preheat the air blown into the furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Hot blast enabled the use of raw anthracite coal, which was difficult to light, in the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Anthracite was first tried successfully by George Crane at Ynyscedwyn Ironworks in south Wales in 1837.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] It was taken up in America by the Lehigh Crane Iron Company at Catasauqua, Pennsylvania, in 1839.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Anthracite use declined when very high capacity blast furnaces requiring coke were built in the 1870s.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The blast furnace remains an important part of modern iron production.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Modern furnaces are highly efficient, including Cowper stoves to pre-heat the blast air and employ recovery systems to extract the heat from the hot gases exiting the furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Competition in industry drives higher production rates.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The largest blast furnace in the world is in South Korea, with a volume around 6,000 m3 (210,000 cu ft).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This is a great increase from the typical 18th-century furnaces, which averaged about 360 tonnes (350 long tons; 400 short tons) per year.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Variations of the blast furnace, such as the Swedish electric blast furnace, have been developed in countries which have no native coal resources.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] According to *Global Energy Monitor*, the blast furnace is likely to become obsolete to meet climate change objectives of reducing carbon dioxide emission, but BHP disagrees.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] An alternative process involving direct reduced iron (DRI) is likely to succeed it, but this also needs to use a blast furnace to melt the iron and remove the gangue (impurities) unless the ore is very high quality.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The oxygen blast furnace (OBF) process, developed from the 1970s to the 1990s, has been extensively studied theoretically because of the potentials of promising energy conservation and CO2 emission reduction.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This type may be the most suitable for use with CCS.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] OBFs are usually combined with top gas recycling.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The problem with this, besides significant oxygen expenditures, is the uneven distribution of gas recycled from the top of the furnace to the middle, which collides with the hot gas from below.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] As of 2023, the technology is only practiced on the experimental level in Sweden, Japan and China.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Blast furnaces are currently rarely used in copper smelting, but modern lead smelting blast furnaces are much shorter than iron blast furnaces and are rectangular in shape.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Modern lead blast furnaces are constructed using water-cooled steel or copper jackets for the walls, and have no refractory linings in the side walls.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The base of the furnace is a hearth of refractory material (bricks or castable refractory).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Lead blast furnaces are often open-topped rather than having the charging bell used in iron blast furnaces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The blast furnace used at the Nyrstar Port Pirie lead smelter differs from most other lead blast furnaces in that it has a double row of tuyeres rather than the single row normally used.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The lower shaft of the furnace has a chair shape with the lower part of the shaft being narrower than the upper.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The lower row of tuyeres being located in the narrow part of the shaft.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This allows the upper part of the shaft to be wider than the standard.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The blast furnaces used in the Imperial Smelting Process ("ISP") were developed from the standard lead blast furnace, but are fully sealed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This is because the zinc produced by these furnaces is recovered as metal from the vapor phase, and the presence of oxygen in the off-gas would result in the formation of zinc oxide.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Blast furnaces used in the ISP have a more intense operation than standard lead blast furnaces, with higher air blast rates per m2 of hearth area and a higher coke consumption.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Zinc production with the ISP is more expensive than with electrolytic zinc plants, so several smelters operating this technology have closed in recent years.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] However, ISP furnaces have the advantage of being able to treat zinc concentrates containing higher levels of lead than can electrolytic zinc plants.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Stone wool or rock wool is a spun mineral fibre used as an insulation product and in hydroponics.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] It is manufactured in a blast furnace fed with diabase rock which contains very low levels of metal oxides.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The resultant slag is drawn off and spun to form the rock wool product.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Very small amounts of metals are also produced which are an unwanted by-product.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Modern furnaces are equipped with an array of supporting facilities to increase efficiency, such as ore storage yards where barges are unloaded.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The raw materials are transferred to the stockhouse complex by ore bridges, or rail hoppers and ore transfer cars.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Rail-mounted scale cars or computer controlled weight hoppers weigh out the various raw materials to yield the desired hot metal and slag chemistry.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The raw materials are brought to the top of the blast furnace via a skip car powered by winches or conveyor belts.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] There are different ways in which the raw materials are charged into the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Some blast furnaces use a "double bell" system where two "bells" are used to control the entry of raw material into the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The purpose of the two bells is to minimize the loss of hot gases in the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] First, the raw materials are emptied into the upper or small bell which then opens to empty the charge into the large bell.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The small bell then closes, to seal the blast furnace, while the large bell rotates to provide specific distribution of materials before dispensing the charge into the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] A more recent design is to use a "bell-less" system.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] These systems use multiple hoppers to contain each raw material, which is then discharged into the blast furnace through valves.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] These valves are more accurate at controlling how much of each constituent is added, as compared to the skip or conveyor system, thereby increasing the efficiency of the furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Some of these bell-less systems also implement a discharge chute in the throat of the furnace (as with the Paul Wurth top) in order to precisely control where the charge is placed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The iron making blast furnace itself is built in the form of a tall structure, lined with refractory brick, and profiled to allow for expansion of the charged materials as they heat during their descent, and subsequent reduction in size as melting starts to occur.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Coke, limestone flux, and iron ore (iron oxide) are charged into the top of the furnace in a precise filling order which helps control gas flow and the chemical reactions inside the furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Four "uptakes" allow the hot, dirty gas high in carbon monoxide content to exit the furnace throat, while "bleeder valves" protect the top of the furnace from sudden gas pressure surges.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The coarse particles in the exhaust gas settle in the "dust catcher" and are dumped into a railroad car or truck for disposal, while the gas itself flows through a venturi scrubber and/or electrostatic precipitators and a gas cooler to reduce the temperature of the cleaned gas.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The "casthouse" at the bottom half of the furnace begins with the "bosh": that portion of the blast furnace above the tuyeres and below the stack.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Shaped like an inverted, truncated cone, it is the part of the blast furnace where ore turns molten.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Next is the bustle pipe (a large-diameter annular pipe to deliver heated air under pressure to the tuyeres) and the equipment for casting the liquid iron and slag.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Once a "taphole" is drilled through the refractory clay plug, liquid iron and slag flow down a trough through a "skimmer" opening, separating the iron and slag.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Modern, larger blast furnaces may have as many as four tapholes and two casthouses.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Once the pig iron and slag has been tapped, the taphole is again plugged with refractory clay.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The tuyeres are used to implement a hot blast, which is used to increase the efficiency of the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The hot blast is directed into the furnace through water-cooled copper nozzles called tuyeres near the base.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The hot blast temperature can be from 900 to 1,300 °C (1,650 to 2,370 °F) depending on the stove design and condition.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Oil, tar, natural gas, powdered coal and oxygen can also be injected into the furnace at tuyere level to combine with the coke to release additional energy and increase the percentage of reducing gases present which is necessary to increase productivity.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The exhaust gasses of a blast furnace are generally cleaned in the dust collector – such as an inertial separator, a baghouse, or an electrostatic precipitator.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Each type of dust collector has strengths and weaknesses – some collect fine particles, some coarse particles, some collect electrically charged particles.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Effective exhaust clearing relies on multiple stages of treatment.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Waste heat is usually collected from the exhaust gases, for example by the use of a Cowper stove, a variety of heat exchanger.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Fossil fuel (coke, natural gas) use in blast furnaces is a source of greenhouse gas emissions and the blast furnace is the most emission intensive stage of the steel making process.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] For every tonne of steel produced in an integrated steel mill, 1.6-2.2 tonnes of CO2 emissions are produced, 70% of which are attributed to the operation of the blast furnace.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Fuels and reductants such as plastic waste, biomass and hydrogen are being used by steelmakers as possible alternatives to fossil fuels, although cost and availability remain a challenge and deployment is limited.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Electric arc furnaces (EAF) are cited as an alternative steel production path which avoids the use of blast furnaces, however, depending on the characteristics of the steel product required the two furnace types are not always interchangeable.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Furthermore, EAFs utilize steel scrap as a feedstock but estimates suggest that there will not be enough scrap available to meet future steel demand.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Using hydrogen gas as a reductant to produce DRI (so called H2-DRI) from iron ore, which is then used as a feedstock for an EAF provides a technologically feasible, low emission alternative to blast furnaces.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The H2-DRI EAF production route is in a fledgling state, with just one plant in operation.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] ULCOS (Ultra Low CO2 Steelmaking) was a European programme exploring processes to reduce blast furnace emissions by at least 50%.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Technologies identified include carbon capture and storage (CCS) and alternative energy sources and reductants such as hydrogen, electricity and biomass.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] For existing blast furnaces, carbon capture, utilisation, and storage (CCUS) is a potential solution to abate emissions.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] This involves capturing CO2 from the furnace's waste gases before they are released, and then either transporting it for permanent underground storage (CCS) or using it to create other products (CCU).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] As of early 2025, no commercial-scale CCUS facility is in full operation on a primary steelmaking plant.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] However, several large-scale pilot and demonstration projects are underway.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] The high costs, estimated at $50 to $100 per tonne of CO2 for industrial sources, and the lack of transport and storage infrastructure remain significant barriers to widespread deployment.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Historically it was normal procedure for a decommissioned blast furnace to be demolished and either replaced with a newer, improved one, or to have the entire site demolished and treated for follow-up use of the area.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] In recent decades, several countries have realized the historic value of blast furnaces and have transformed them into museums.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/blast-furnace] Examples can be found in the Czech Republic, France, Germany, Japan, Luxembourg, Poland, Romania, Mexico, Russia, Spain, United Kingdom, and United States.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] The partnership was formed in 1775 to exploit Watt's patent for a steam engine with a separate condenser.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] This made much more efficient use of its fuel than the older Newcomen engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] Initially the business was based at the Soho Manufactory near Boulton's Soho House on the southern edge of the then-rural parish of Handsworth.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] However most of the components for their engines were made by others, for example the cylinders by John Wilkinson.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] In 1795, they began to make steam engines themselves at their Soho Foundry in Smethwick, near Birmingham, England.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] Between 1775 and 1800, Boulton and Watt produced 496 engines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] The partnership was passed to two of their sons in 1800.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] William Murdoch was made a partner of the firm in 1810, where he remained until his retirement 20 years later at the age of 76.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] The firm lasted over 120 years, albeit renamed "James Watt & Co." in 1849, and was still making steam engines in 1895, when it was sold to W & T Avery Ltd.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] For ten years their banker in London was Charlotte Matthews after her husband died in 1792.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] A woman banker was unusual but she became a close confidante, holidaying with Boulton, and she lent them enormous sums to fund their endeavours.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] When she died aged 43 in 1802 her business was run by the Boulton and Watt families.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] The business trained young engineers who went on to achieve notability.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] Among the names which were employed there in the eighteenth century were James Law, Peter Ewart, William Brunton, Isaac Perrins, William Murdoch, James Watt, Jr., William Playfair, and John Southern.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] The firm left an extremely detailed archive of its activities, which was given to the city of Birmingham in 1911 and is kept at the Library of Birmingham.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] An additional archive was donated to the Boulton and Watt collection in 2015 including a thesis.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/boulton-watt] The archive contains: Display folders containing text and varieties of drawings.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Improvements to the steam engine were some of the most important technologies of the Industrial Revolution, although steam did not replace water power in importance in Britain until after the Industrial Revolution.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Early mills had run successfully with water power, but by using a steam engine a factory could be located anywhere, not just close to a water source.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Water power varied with the seasons and was not always available.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In 1776 Watt formed an engine-building and engineering partnership with manufacturer Matthew Boulton.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The partnership of Boulton & Watt became one of the most important businesses of the Industrial Revolution and served as a kind of creative technical centre for much of the British economy.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The partners solved technical problems and spread the solutions to other companies.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Similar firms did the same thing in other industries and were especially important in the machine tool industry.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] These interactions between companies were important because they reduced the amount of research time and expense that each business had to spend working with its own resources.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The technological advances of the Industrial Revolution happened more quickly because firms often shared information, which they then could use to create new techniques or products.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The development of the stationary steam engine was a very important early element of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] However, it should be remembered that for most of the period of the Industrial Revolution, the majority of industries still relied on wind and water power as well as horse and man-power for driving small machines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The industrial use of steam power started with Thomas Savery in 1698.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] He constructed and patented in London the first engine, which he called the "Miner's Friend" since he intended it to pump water from mines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Early versions used a soldered copper boiler which burst easily at low steam pressures.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Later versions with iron boiler were capable of raising water about 46 meters (150 feet).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The Savery engine had no moving parts other than hand-operated valves.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The engine was used as a low-lift water pump in a few mines and numerous water works, but it was not a success since it was limited in pumping height and prone to boiler explosions.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The first practical mechanical steam engine was introduced by Thomas Newcomen in 1712.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Newcomen apparently conceived his machine independently of Savery, but as the latter had taken out a wide-ranging patent, Newcomen and his associates were obliged to come to an arrangement with him, marketing the engine until 1733 under a joint patent.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Newcomen's engine appears to have been based on Papin's experiments carried out 30 years earlier, and employed a piston and cylinder, one end of which was open to the atmosphere above the piston.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The engine's downward power stroke raised the pump, priming it and preparing the pumping stroke.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] At first the phases were controlled by hand, but within ten years an escapement mechanism had been devised worked by of a vertical *plug tree* suspended from the rocking beam which rendered the engine self-acting.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] A number of Newcomen engines were successfully put to use in Britain for draining hitherto unworkable deep mines, with the engine on the surface; these were large machines, requiring a lot of capital to build, and produced about 5 hp.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] They were extremely inefficient by modern standards, but when located where coal was cheap at pit heads, opened up a great expansion in coal mining by allowing mines to go deeper.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Despite their disadvantages, Newcomen engines were reliable and easy to maintain and continued to be used in the coalfields until the early decades of the nineteenth century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] By 1729, when Newcomen died, his engines had spread to France, Germany, Austria, Hungary and Sweden.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] A total of 110 are known to have been built by 1733 when the joint patent expired, of which 14 were abroad.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In the 1770s, the engineer John Smeaton built some very large examples and introduced a number of improvements.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] A total of 1,454 engines had been built by 1800.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] A fundamental change in working principles was brought about by James Watt.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] These improvements increased engine efficiency by a factor of about five, saving 75% on coal costs.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The Newcomen engine could not, at the time, be easily adapted to drive a rotating wheel, although Wasborough and Pickard did succeed in doing so in about 1780.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] However, by 1783 the more economical Watt steam engine had been fully developed into a double-acting rotative type with a centrifugal governor, parallel motion and flywheel, which meant that it could be used to directly drive the rotary machinery of a factory or mill.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Both of Watt's basic engine types were commercially very successful.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] By 1800, the firm Boulton & Watt had constructed 496 engines, with 164 driving reciprocating pumps, 24 serving blast furnaces, and 308 powering mill machinery; most of the engines generated from 5 to 10 hp.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] An estimate of the total power that could be produced by all these engines was about 11,200 hp.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This was still only a fraction of the total power-generating capacity in Britain by waterwheels (120,000 hp) and by windmills (15,000 hp); however, water and wind power were seasonably variable.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Newcomen and other steam engines generated at the same time about 24,000 hp.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The development of machine tools, such as the lathe, planing and shaping machines powered by these engines, enabled all the metal parts of the engines to be easily and accurately cut and in turn made it possible to build larger and more powerful engines.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Until about 1800, the most common pattern of steam engine was the beam engine, built as an integral part of a stone or brick engine-house, but soon various patterns of self-contained portative engines (readily removable, but not on wheels) were developed, such as the table engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This allowed an engine and boiler to be combined into a single unit compact and light enough to be used on mobile road and rail locomotives and steam boats.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Trevithick was a man of versatile talents, and his activities were not confined to small applications.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Trevithick developed his large Cornish boiler with an internal flue from about 1812.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The Cornish engine was developed in the 1810s for pumping mines in Cornwall.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] It was the result of using the exhaust of a high-pressure engine to power a condensing engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The Cornish engine was notable for its relatively high efficiency.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The last major improvement to the steam engine was the Corliss engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Named after its inventor, George Henry Corliss, this stationary steam engine was introduced to the world in 1849.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] While the engine was loosely based on existing steam engines, keeping the simple piston-flywheel design, the majority of these features were brought about by the engine's unique valves and valve gears.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Unlike most engines employed during the era that used mainly slide-valve gears, Corliss created his own system that used a wrist plate to control a number of different valves.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Each cylinder was equipped with four valves, with exhaust and inlet valves at both ends of the cylinder.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Through a precisely tuned series of events opening and closing these valves, steam is admitted and released at a precise rate, allowing for linear piston motion.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This provided the engine's most notable feature, the automatic variable cut-off mechanism.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This mechanism is what allowed the engine to maintain a set speed in response to varying loads without losing efficiency, stalling, or being damaged.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Using a series of cam gears, which could adjust valve timing (essentially acting as a throttle), the engine's speed and horsepower was adjusted.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This proved extremely useful for most of the engine's applications.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In the textile industry, it allowed for production at much higher speeds while lowering the likelihood that threads would break.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In metallurgy, the extreme and abrupt variations of load experienced in rolling mills were also countered by the technology.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] These examples demonstrate that the Corliss engine was able to lead to much higher rates of production, while preventing costly damages to machinery and materials.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Corliss kept a detailed record of the production, collective horsepower, and sales of his engines up until the patent expired.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] He did this for a number of reasons, including tracking those who infringed on the patent rights, maintenance and upgrade details, and especially as data used to extend the patent.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] With this data, a more clear understanding of the engine's influence is provided.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] By 1869, nearly 1200 engines had been sold, totaling 118,500 horsepower.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Another estimated 60,000 horsepower was being utilized by engines that were created by manufacturers infringing on Corliss's patent, bringing the total horsepower to roughly 180,000.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This relatively small number of engines produced 15% of the United States’ total 1.2 million horsepower.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The mean horsepower for all Corliss engines in 1870 was 100, while the mean for all steam engines (including Corliss engines) was 30.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Some very large engines even allowed for applications as large as 1,400 horsepower.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Many were convinced of the Corliss engine's benefits, but adoption was slow due to patent protection.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] When Corliss was denied a patent extension in 1870, it became a prevalent model for stationary engines in the industrial sector.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] By the end of the 19th century, the engine was already having a major influence on the manufacturing sector, where it made up only 10% of the sector's engines, but produced 46% of the horsepower.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The engine also became a model of efficiency outside of the textile industry, as it was used for pumping the waterways of Pawtucket, Rhode Island in 1878, and played an essential role in the expansion of the railroad by allowing for very large-scale operations in rolling mills.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Many steam engines of the 19th century have been replaced, destroyed, or repurposed, but the longevity of the Corliss engine is apparent today in select distilleries, where they are still used as a power source.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In the mid-1750s, the steam engine was applied to the water power-constrained iron, copper and lead industries for powering blast bellows.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] These industries were located near the mines, some of which were using steam engines for mine pumping.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Steam engines were too powerful for leather bellows, so cast iron blowing cylinders were developed in 1768.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Steam-powered blast furnaces achieved higher temperatures, allowing the use of more lime in iron blast furnace feed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] (Lime-rich slag was not free-flowing at the previously used temperatures.) With a sufficient lime ratio, sulfur from coal or coke fuel reacts with the slag so that the sulfur does not contaminate the iron.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Coal and coke were cheaper and more abundant fuel.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] As a result, iron production rose significantly during the last decades of the 18th century.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Water power, the world's preceding supply of power, continued to be an essential power source even during the height of steam engine popularity.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The steam engine, however, provided many benefits that couldn't be realized by relying solely on water power, allowing it to quickly become industrialised nations' dominant power source (rising from 5% to 80% of the total power in the US from 1838-1860).
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] While many consider the potential for an increase in power generated to be the dominant benefit (with the average horsepower of steam-powered mills producing four times the power of water-powered mills), others favor the potential for agglomeration.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Steam engines made it possible to easily work, produce, market, specialize, viably expand westward without having to worry about the less abundant presence of waterways, and live in communities that weren't geographically isolated in proximity to rivers and streams.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Cities and towns were now built around factories where steam engines served as the foundation for the livelihood of many of the citizens.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In some counties where the establishments utilized steam power, population growths were even seen to increase.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] These steam-powered towns encouraged growth locally and on the national scale, further validating the economic importance of the steam engine.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This period of economic growth, which was ushered in by the introduction and adoption of the steamboat, was one of the greatest ever experienced in the United States.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Robert Fulton, Robert Livingston and Henry Shreve were all big contributors to the introduction of the steamboat to the American public.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Around 1815, steamboats began to replace barges and flatboats in the transport of goods around the United States.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Prior to the steamboat, rivers were generally only used in transporting goods from east to west, and from north to south as fighting the current was very difficult and often impossible.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Non-powered boats and rafts were assembled up-stream, would carry their cargo down stream, and would often be disassembled at the end of their journey; with their remains being used to construct homes and commercial buildings.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Following the advent of the steamboat, the United States saw an incredible growth in the transportation of goods and people, which was key in westward expansion.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Prior to the steamboat, it could take between three and four months to make the passage from New Orleans to Louisville, averaging twenty miles a day.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] With the steamboat this time was reduced drastically with trips ranging from twenty-five to thirty-five days.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This was especially beneficial to farmers as their crops could now be transported elsewhere to be sold.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The steamboat also allowed for increased specialization.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Sugar and cotton were shipped up north while goods like poultry, grain, and pork were shipped south.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Unfortunately, the steamboat also aided in the internal slave trade.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] With the steamboat came the need for an improved river system.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The natural river system had features that either wasn't compatible with steamboat travel or was only available during certain months when rivers were higher.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Some obstacles included rapids, sand bars, shallow waters and waterfalls.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] To overcome these natural obstacles, a network of canals, locks and dams were constructed.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This increased demand for labor spurred tremendous job growth along the rivers.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The economic benefits of the steamboat extended far beyond the construction of the ships themselves, and the goods they transported.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] These ships led directly to growth in the coal and insurance industries, along with creating demand for repair facilities along the rivers.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Additionally the demand for goods in general increased as the steamboat made transport to new destinations both wide reaching and efficient.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] After the steamboat was invented and achieved a number of successful trials, it was quickly adopted and led to an even quicker change in the way of water transport.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In 1814, the city of New Orleans recorded 21 steamboat arrivals, but over the course of the following 20 years that number exploded to more than 1200.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The steamboat's role as a major transportation source was secured.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The transport sector saw enormous growth following the steam engine's application, leading to major innovations in canals, steamboats, and railroads.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The steamboat and canal system revolutionized trade of the United States.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] As the steamboats gained popularity, enthusiasm grew for the building of canals.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] In 1816, the US had only 100 miles of canals.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] This needed to change, however, as the potential increase in traded goods from east to west convinced many that canals were a necessary connection between the Mississippi–Ohio waterways with the Great Lakes.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] The use of steam engines on railroads proved to be extraordinary in the fact that now you could have large amounts of goods and raw materials delivered to cities and factories alike.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Trains could deliver these to places far away at a fraction of the cost of traveling by wagon.
[src:steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution/steam-power-during-the-industrial-revolution] Railroad tracks, which were already in use in mines and various other situations, became the new means of transportation after the first locomotive was invented.
